#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:3 original/man1/lesskey.1:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "NAME"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:5
msgid "less - display the contents of a file in a terminal"
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:5
#, no-wrap
msgid "SYNOPSIS"
msgstr ""

#.  AT&T man(7) macros accept six arguments at most.
#.  Work around bugs in the man(7) font selection macros in Solaris 10,
#.  Plan 9, and DWB 3.3 troffs.
#. .RB [ "\-\[dq]\c"\" works with groff, mandoc, and Heirloom Doctools
#.  Restore the adjustment mode.
#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:55
msgid ""
"B<less> [B<->[B<+>]B<aABcCdeEfFgGiIJKLmMnNqQrRsSuUVwWX\\*~>] [B<-b\\ "
">I<size>] [B<-D\\ >I<color>] [B<-h\\ >I<lines>] [B<-j\\ >I<line>] [B<-k\\ "
">I<key-file>] [B<->{B<o>|B<O>} I<log-file>] [B<-p\\ >I<pattern ]> [B<-P\\ "
">I<prompt>] [B<-t\\ >I<tag>] [B<-T\\ >I<tags-file>] [B<-x\\ "
">I<tab>[{B<,>I<tab>}.\\|.\\|.]]\\& [B<-y\\ >I<lines>] [B<-z\\ >I<lines>] "
"[B<->I<lines>] [B<-\">I<cc>] [B<-#\\ >I<shift>] [B<+>I<less-command>] "
"[B<-->] [I<file>\\ .\\|.\\|.]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:58
msgid "B<less -?>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:60
msgid "B<less --help>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:62
msgid "B<less -V>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:64
msgid "B<less --version>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:66
msgid ""
"(See the OPTIONS section for alternate option syntax with long option "
"names.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:67 original/man1/lesskey.1:41
#, no-wrap
msgid "DESCRIPTION"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:82
msgid ""
"B<Less> is a program similar to B<more>(1), but it has many more features.  "
"B<Less> does not have to read the entire input file before starting, so with "
"large input files it starts up faster than text editors like B<vi>(1).  "
"B<Less> uses termcap (or terminfo on some systems), so it can run on a "
"variety of terminals.  There is even limited support for hardcopy "
"terminals.  (On a hardcopy terminal, lines which should be printed at the "
"top of the screen are prefixed with a caret.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:82
#, no-wrap
msgid "COMMANDS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:90
msgid ""
"Commands are based on both B<more> and B<vi>.  Commands may be preceded by a "
"decimal number, called N in the descriptions below.  The number is used by "
"some commands, as indicated."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:94
msgid ""
"In the following descriptions, \\*^X means control-X.  ESC stands for the "
"ESCAPE key; for example ESC-v means the two character sequence \"ESCAPE\", "
"then \"v\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:94
#, no-wrap
msgid "h or H"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:97
msgid ""
"Help: display a summary of these commands.  If you forget all the other "
"commands, remember this one."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:97
#, no-wrap
msgid "SPACE or \\*^V or f or \\*^F"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:103
msgid ""
"Scroll forward N lines, default one window (see option B<-z> below).  If N "
"is more than the screen size, only the final screenful is displayed.  "
"Warning: some systems use \\*^V as a special literalization character."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:103 original/man1/lesskey.1:214
#, no-wrap
msgid "z"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:105
msgid "Like SPACE, but if N is specified, it becomes the new window size."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:105
#, no-wrap
msgid "ENTER or RETURN or \\*^N or e or \\*^E or j or \\*^J"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:108
msgid ""
"Scroll forward N lines, default 1.  The entire N lines are displayed, even "
"if N is more than the screen size."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:108
#, no-wrap
msgid "d or \\*^D"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:112
msgid ""
"Scroll forward N lines, default one half of the screen size.  If N is "
"specified, it becomes the new default for subsequent d and u commands."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:112
#, no-wrap
msgid "b or \\*^B or ESC-v"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:117
msgid ""
"Scroll backward N lines, default one window (see option B<-z> below).  If N "
"is more than the screen size, only the final screenful is displayed."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:117 original/man1/less.1:961 original/man1/less.1:2520
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:215
#, no-wrap
msgid "w"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:119
msgid "Like ESC-v, but if N is specified, it becomes the new window size."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:119
#, no-wrap
msgid "y or \\*^Y or \\*^P or k or \\*^K"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:123
msgid ""
"Scroll backward N lines, default 1.  The entire N lines are displayed, even "
"if N is more than the screen size.  Warning: some systems use \\*^Y as a "
"special job control character."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:123
#, no-wrap
msgid "u or \\*^U"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:127
msgid ""
"Scroll backward N lines, default one half of the screen size.  If N is "
"specified, it becomes the new default for subsequent d and u commands."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:127 original/man1/lesskey.1:198
#, no-wrap
msgid "J"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:129
msgid "Like j, but continues to scroll beyond the end of the file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:129
#, no-wrap
msgid "K or Y"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:131
msgid "Like k, but continues to scroll beyond the beginning of the file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:131
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-SPACE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:134
msgid ""
"Like SPACE, but scrolls a full screenful, even if it reaches the end of the "
"file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:134
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-b"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:137
msgid ""
"Like b, but scrolls a full screenful, even if it reaches the beginning of "
"the file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:137
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-j"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:140
msgid ""
"Scroll forward N file lines, default 1.  A file line is a complete line in "
"the file, terminated by a newline."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:140
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-k"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:142
msgid "Scroll backwards N file lines, default 1."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:142
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-) or RIGHTARROW"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:153
msgid ""
"Scroll horizontally right N characters, default half the screen width (see "
"the B<-#> option).  If a number N is specified, it becomes the default for "
"future RIGHTARROW and LEFTARROW commands.  While the text is scrolled, it "
"acts as though the B<-S> option (chop lines) were in effect."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:153
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-( or LEFTARROW"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:160
msgid ""
"Scroll horizontally left N characters, default half the screen width (see "
"the B<-#> option).  If a number N is specified, it becomes the default for "
"future RIGHTARROW and LEFTARROW commands."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:160
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-} or \\*^RIGHTARROW or SHIFT-RIGHTARROW"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:162
msgid "Scroll horizontally right to show the end of the longest displayed line."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:162
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-{ or \\*^LEFTARROW or SHIFT-LEFTARROW"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:164
msgid "Scroll horizontally left back to the first column."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:164
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^END or SHIFT-END"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:167
msgid ""
"Go to line N in the file, default the end of the file, and scroll "
"horizontally right to show the end of the longest displayed line."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:167
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^HOME or SHIFT-HOME"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:170
msgid ""
"Go to line N in the file, default 1 (beginning of file), and scroll "
"horizontally left back to the first column."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:170
#, no-wrap
msgid "r or \\*^R or \\*^L"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:172
msgid "Repaint the screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:172 original/man1/less.1:890
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:223
#, no-wrap
msgid "R"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:176
msgid ""
"Repaint the screen, discarding any buffered input.  That is, reload the "
"current file.  Useful if the file is changing while it is being viewed."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:176 original/man1/lesskey.1:220
#, no-wrap
msgid "F"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:195
msgid ""
"Scroll forward, and keep trying to read when the end of file is reached.  "
"Normally this command would be used when already at the end of the file.  It "
"is a way to monitor the tail of a file which is growing while it is being "
"viewed.  (The behavior is similar to the \"tail -f\" command.)  To stop "
"waiting for more data, enter the interrupt character (usually \\*^C).  On "
"systems which support B<poll>(2)  you can also use \\*^X or the character "
"specified by the B<--intr> option.  If the input is a pipe and the "
"B<--exit-follow-on-close> option is in effect, B<less> will automatically "
"stop waiting for data when the input side of the pipe is closed."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:195
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-f"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:198
msgid ""
"Like F, but each time a line is found which matches the last search pattern, "
"the terminal bell is rung."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:198
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-F"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:202
msgid ""
"Like F, but as soon as a line is found which matches the last search "
"pattern, the terminal bell is rung and forward scrolling stops."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:202
#, no-wrap
msgid "g or E<lt> or ESC-E<lt> or HOME"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:205
msgid ""
"Go to line N in the file, default 1 (beginning of file).  (Warning: this may "
"be slow if N is large.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:205
#, no-wrap
msgid "G or E<gt> or ESC-E<gt> or END"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:210
msgid ""
"Go to line N in the file, default the end of the file.  (Warning: this may "
"be slow if N is large, or if N is not specified and standard input, rather "
"than a file, is being read.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:210
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-G"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:213
msgid ""
"Same as G, except if no number N is specified and the input is standard "
"input, goes to the last line which is currently buffered."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:213
#, no-wrap
msgid "p or %"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:216
msgid ""
"Go to a position N percent into the file.  N should be between 0 and 100, "
"and may contain a decimal point."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:216 original/man1/less.1:888
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:261
#, no-wrap
msgid "P"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:218
msgid "Go to the line containing byte offset N in the file."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:218 original/man1/lesskey.1:250
#, no-wrap
msgid "{"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:226
msgid ""
"If a left curly bracket appears in the top line displayed on the screen, the "
"{ command will go to the matching right curly bracket.  The matching right "
"curly bracket is positioned on the bottom line of the screen.  If there is "
"more than one left curly bracket on the top line, a number N may be used to "
"specify the N-th bracket on the line."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:226 original/man1/lesskey.1:251
#, no-wrap
msgid "}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:234
msgid ""
"If a right curly bracket appears in the bottom line displayed on the screen, "
"the } command will go to the matching left curly bracket.  The matching left "
"curly bracket is positioned on the top line of the screen.  If there is more "
"than one right curly bracket on the bottom line, a number N may be used to "
"specify the N-th bracket on the line."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:234 original/man1/lesskey.1:252
#, no-wrap
msgid "("
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:236
msgid "Like {, but applies to parentheses rather than curly brackets."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:236 original/man1/lesskey.1:253
#, no-wrap
msgid ")"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:238
msgid "Like }, but applies to parentheses rather than curly brackets."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:238 original/man1/lesskey.1:254
#, no-wrap
msgid "["
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:240
msgid "Like {, but applies to square brackets rather than curly brackets."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:240 original/man1/lesskey.1:255
#, no-wrap
msgid "]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:242
msgid "Like }, but applies to square brackets rather than curly brackets."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:242
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-\\*^F"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:248
msgid ""
"Followed by two characters, acts like {, but uses the two characters as open "
"and close brackets, respectively.  For example, \"ESC \\*^F E<lt> E<gt>\" "
"could be used to go forward to the E<gt> which matches the E<lt> in the top "
"displayed line."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:248
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-\\*^B"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:254
msgid ""
"Followed by two characters, acts like }, but uses the two characters as open "
"and close brackets, respectively.  For example, \"ESC \\*^B E<lt> E<gt>\" "
"could be used to go backward to the E<lt> which matches the E<gt> in the "
"bottom displayed line."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:254 original/man1/less.1:957 original/man1/less.1:1649
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:275
#, no-wrap
msgid "m"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:261
msgid ""
"Followed by any lowercase or uppercase letter, marks the first displayed "
"line with that letter.  If the status column is enabled via the B<-J> "
"option, the status column shows the marked line."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:261 original/man1/less.1:882
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:276
#, no-wrap
msgid "M"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:264
msgid ""
"Acts like m, except the last displayed line is marked rather than the first "
"displayed line."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:264
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*'"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:279
msgid ""
"(Single quote.)  Followed by any lowercase or uppercase letter, returns to "
"the position which was previously marked with that letter.  Followed by "
"another single quote, returns to the position at which the last \"large\" "
"movement command was executed.  Followed by a \\*^ or $, jumps to the "
"beginning or end of the file respectively.  Marks are preserved when a new "
"file is examined within a single invocation of B<less>, so the \\*' command "
"can be used to switch between input files.  The B<--save-marks> option "
"causes marks to be preserved across different invocations of B<less>."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:279 original/man1/lesskey.1:279
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^X\\*^X"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:281
msgid "Same as single quote."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:281
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-m"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:284
msgid ""
"Followed by any lowercase or uppercase letter, clears the mark identified by "
"that letter."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:284
#, no-wrap
msgid "/pattern"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:299
msgid ""
"Search forward in the file for the N-th line containing the pattern.  N "
"defaults to 1.  The pattern is a regular expression, as recognized by the "
"regular expression library supplied by your system.  By default, searching "
"is case-sensitive (uppercase and lowercase are considered different); the "
"B<-i> option can be used to change this.  The search starts at the first "
"line displayed (but see the B<-a> and B<-j> options, which change this)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:303
msgid ""
"Certain characters are special if entered at the beginning of the pattern; "
"they modify the type of search rather than become part of the pattern:"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:304 original/man1/less.1:360 original/man1/less.1:442
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^N or !"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:306 original/man1/less.1:362
msgid "Search for lines which do NOT match the pattern."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:306 original/man1/less.1:362
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^E or *"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:311
msgid ""
"Search multiple files.  That is, if the search reaches the END of the "
"current file without finding a match, the search continues in the next file "
"in the command line list."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:311 original/man1/less.1:367
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^F or @"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:320
msgid ""
"Begin the search at the first line of the FIRST file in the command line "
"list, regardless of what is currently displayed on the screen or the "
"settings of the B<-a> or B<-j> options."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:320 original/man1/less.1:376
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:195
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^K"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:323
msgid ""
"Highlight any text which matches the pattern on the current screen, but "
"don't move to the first match (KEEP current position)."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:323 original/man1/less.1:378 original/man1/less.1:444
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:225
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^R"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:326 original/man1/less.1:447
msgid ""
"Don't interpret regular expression metacharacters; that is, do a simple "
"textual comparison."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:326 original/man1/less.1:380
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^S"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:339
msgid ""
"Followed by a digit N between 1 and 5.  Only text which has a non-empty "
"match for the N-th parenthesized SUB-PATTERN will be considered to match the "
"pattern.  For example, searching for \"(abc)|(def)\" modified with \\*^S1 "
"would search for instances of \"abc\", but would highlight instances of both "
"\"abc\" and \"def\".  (Supported only if B<less> is built with one of the "
"regular expression libraries B<posix>, B<pcre>, or B<pcre2>.)  Multiple "
"\\*^S modifiers can be specified, to match more than one sub-pattern."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:339 original/man1/less.1:382
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^W"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:345
msgid ""
"WRAP around the current file.  That is, if the search reaches the end of the "
"current file without finding a match, the search continues from the first "
"line of the current file up to the line where it started.  If the \\*^W "
"modifier is set, the \\*^E modifier is ignored."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:345 original/man1/less.1:387 original/man1/less.1:2114
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:226
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^L"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:348
msgid ""
"The next character is taken literally; that is, it becomes part of the "
"pattern even if it is one of the above search modifier characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:349
#, no-wrap
msgid "?pattern"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:357
msgid ""
"Search backward in the file for the N-th line containing the pattern.  The "
"search starts at the last line displayed (but see the B<-a> and B<-j> "
"options, which change this)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:359 original/man1/less.1:441
msgid "Certain characters are special as in the / command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:367
msgid ""
"Search multiple files.  That is, if the search reaches the beginning of the "
"current file without finding a match, the search continues in the previous "
"file in the command line list."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:376
msgid ""
"Begin the search at the last line of the last file in the command line list, "
"regardless of what is currently displayed on the screen or the settings of "
"the B<-a> or B<-j> options."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:378 original/man1/less.1:380 original/man1/less.1:382
#: original/man1/less.1:389
msgid "As in forward searches."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:387
msgid ""
"WRAP around the current file.  That is, if the search reaches the beginning "
"of the current file without finding a match, the search continues from the "
"last line of the current file up to the line where it started."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:390
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-/pattern"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:392
msgid "Same as \"/*\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:392
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-?pattern"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:394
msgid "Same as \"?*\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:394 original/man1/lesskey.1:270
#, no-wrap
msgid "n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:405
msgid ""
"Repeat previous search, for N-th line containing the last pattern.  If the "
"previous search was modified by \\*^N, the search is made for the N-th line "
"NOT containing the pattern.  If the previous search was modified by \\*^E, "
"the search continues in the next (or previous) file if not satisfied in the "
"current file.  If the previous search was modified by \\*^R, the search is "
"done without using regular expressions.  If the previous search was modified "
"by \\*^W, the search wraps at the end (or beginning) of the file.  There is "
"no effect if the previous search was modified by \\*^F or \\*^K."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:405 original/man1/less.1:884
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:272
#, no-wrap
msgid "N"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:407
msgid "Repeat previous search, but in the reverse direction."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:407
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:410
msgid ""
"Repeat previous search, but crossing file boundaries.  The effect is as if "
"the previous search were modified by *."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:410
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-N"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:413
msgid ""
"Repeat previous search, but in the reverse direction and crossing file "
"boundaries."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:413
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-u"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:423
msgid ""
"Undo search highlighting.  Turn off highlighting of strings matching the "
"current search pattern.  If highlighting is already off because of a "
"previous ESC-u command, turn highlighting back on.  Any search command will "
"also turn highlighting back on.  (Highlighting can also be disabled by "
"toggling the B<-G> option; in that case search commands do not turn "
"highlighting back on.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:423
#, no-wrap
msgid "ESC-U"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:429
msgid ""
"Like ESC-u but also clears the saved search pattern.  If the status column "
"is enabled via the B<-J> option, this clears all search matches marked in "
"the status column."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:429
#, no-wrap
msgid "&pattern"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:439
msgid ""
"Display only lines which match the pattern; lines which do not match the "
"pattern are not displayed.  If pattern is empty (if you type & immediately "
"followed by ENTER), any filtering is turned off, and all lines are "
"displayed.  While filtering is in effect, an ampersand is displayed at the "
"beginning of the prompt, as a reminder that some lines in the file may be "
"hidden.  Multiple & commands may be entered, in which case only lines which "
"match all of the patterns will be displayed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:444
msgid "Display only lines which do NOT match the pattern."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:448
#, no-wrap
msgid ":e [filename]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:469
msgid ""
"Examine a new file.  If the filename is missing, the \"current\" file (see "
"the :n and :p commands below) from the list of files in the command line is "
"re-examined.  A percent sign (%) in the filename is replaced by the name of "
"the current file.  A pound sign (#) is replaced by the name of the "
"previously examined file.  However, two consecutive percent signs are simply "
"replaced with a single percent sign.  This allows you to enter a filename "
"that contains a percent sign in the name.  Similarly, two consecutive pound "
"signs are replaced with a single pound sign.  The filename is inserted into "
"the command line list of files so that it can be seen by subsequent :n and "
":p commands.  If the filename consists of several files, they are all "
"inserted into the list of files and the first one is examined.  If the "
"filename contains one or more spaces, the entire filename should be enclosed "
"in double quotes (also see the B<-\\[dq]> option)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:469
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^X\\*^V or E"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:473
msgid ""
"Same as :e.  Warning: some systems use \\*^V as a special literalization "
"character.  On such systems, you may not be able to use \\*^V."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:473 original/man1/lesskey.1:283
#, no-wrap
msgid ":n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:476
msgid ""
"Examine the next file (from the list of files given in the command line).  "
"If a number N is specified, the N-th next file is examined."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:476 original/man1/lesskey.1:284
#, no-wrap
msgid ":p"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:479
msgid ""
"Examine the previous file in the command line list.  If a number N is "
"specified, the N-th previous file is examined."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:479 original/man1/lesskey.1:295
#, no-wrap
msgid ":x"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:482
msgid ""
"Examine the first file in the command line list.  If a number N is "
"specified, the N-th file in the list is examined."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:482 original/man1/lesskey.1:296
#, no-wrap
msgid ":d"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:484
msgid "Remove the current file from the list of files."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:484 original/man1/lesskey.1:293
#, no-wrap
msgid "t"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:489
msgid ""
"Go to the next tag, if there were more than one matches for the current "
"tag.  See the B<-t> option for more details about tags."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:489 original/man1/lesskey.1:294
#, no-wrap
msgid "T"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:491
msgid ""
"Go to the previous tag, if there were more than one matches for the current "
"tag."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:491
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^O\\*^N or \\*^On"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:493
msgid "Search forward in the file for the N-th next OSC 8 hyperlink."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:493
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^O\\*^P or \\*^Op"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:495
msgid "Search backward in the file for the N-th previous OSC 8 hyperlink."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:495
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^O\\*^L or \\*^Ol"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:497
msgid "Jump to the currently selected OSC 8 hyperlink."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:497
#, no-wrap
msgid "= or \\*^G or :f"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:504
msgid ""
"Prints some information about the file being viewed, including its name and "
"the line number and byte offset of the bottom line being displayed.  If "
"possible, it also prints the length of the file, the number of lines in the "
"file and the percent of the file above the last displayed line."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:504 original/man1/lesskey.1:297
#, no-wrap
msgid "-"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:521
msgid ""
"Followed by one of the command line option letters (see OPTIONS below), this "
"will change the setting of that option and print a message describing the "
"new setting.  If a \\*^P (CONTROL-P) is entered immediately after the dash, "
"the setting of the option is changed but no message is printed.  If the "
"option letter has a numeric value (such as B<-b> or B<-h>), or a string "
"value (such as B<-P> or B<-t>), a new value may be entered after the option "
"letter.  If no new value is entered, a message describing the current "
"setting is printed and nothing is changed."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:521
#, no-wrap
msgid "--"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:529
msgid ""
"Like the - command, but takes a long option name (see OPTIONS below)  rather "
"than a single option letter.  Press ENTER or RETURN after typing the option "
"name to change it.  You can enter just the beginning of an option name, then "
"press TAB to find all option names which begin with that string.  A \\*^P "
"immediately after the second dash suppresses printing of a message "
"describing the new setting, as in the - command."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:529
#, no-wrap
msgid "-+"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:538
msgid ""
"Followed by one of the command line option letters this will reset the "
"option to its default setting and print a message describing the new "
"setting.  (The \"-+I<X>\" command does the same thing as \\[dq]B<-+X>\\[dq] "
"on the command line.)  This does not work for string-valued options."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:538
#, no-wrap
msgid "--+"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:541
msgid ""
"Like the -+ command, but takes a long option name rather than a single "
"option letter."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:541
#, no-wrap
msgid "-!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:546
msgid ""
"Followed by one of the command line option letters, this will reset the "
"option to the \"opposite\" of its default setting and print a message "
"describing the new setting.  This does not work for numeric or string-valued "
"options."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:546
#, no-wrap
msgid "--!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:549
msgid ""
"Like the -!\\& command, but takes a long option name rather than a single "
"option letter."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:549
#, no-wrap
msgid "_"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:554
msgid ""
"(Underscore.)  Followed by one of the command line option letters, this will "
"print a message describing the current setting of that option.  The setting "
"of the option is not changed."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:554
#, no-wrap
msgid "__"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:559
msgid ""
"(Double underscore.)  Like the _ (underscore) command, but takes a long "
"option name rather than a single option letter.  You must press ENTER or "
"RETURN after typing the option name."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:559
#, no-wrap
msgid "+cmd"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:565
msgid ""
"Causes the specified cmd to be executed each time a new file is examined.  "
"For example, +G causes B<less> to initially display each file starting at "
"the end rather than the beginning."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:565 original/man1/lesskey.1:329
#, no-wrap
msgid "V"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:569
msgid "Prints the version number of B<less> being run."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:569
#, no-wrap
msgid "q or Q or :q or :Q or ZZ"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:572
msgid "Exits B<less>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:576
msgid ""
"The following seven commands may or may not be valid, depending on your "
"particular installation."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:577 original/man1/lesskey.1:305
#, no-wrap
msgid "v"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:583
msgid ""
"Invokes an editor to edit the current file being viewed.  The editor is "
"taken from the environment variable VISUAL if defined, or EDITOR if VISUAL "
"is not defined, or defaults to \"vi\" if neither VISUAL nor EDITOR is "
"defined.  See also the discussion of LESSEDIT under the section on PROMPTS "
"below."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:583
#, no-wrap
msgid "! shell-command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:595
msgid ""
"Invokes a shell to run the shell-command given.  A percent sign (%) in the "
"command is replaced by the name of the current file.  A pound sign (#) is "
"replaced by the name of the previously examined file.  \"!!\" repeats the "
"last shell command.  \"!\" with no shell command invokes an interactive "
"shell.  If a \\*^P (CONTROL-P) is entered immediately after the !, no "
"\"done\" message is printed after the shell command is executed.  On Unix "
"systems, the shell is taken from the environment variable SHELL, or defaults "
"to \"sh\".  On MS-DOS, Windows, and OS/2 systems, the shell is the normal "
"command processor."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:595
#, no-wrap
msgid "# shell-command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:599
msgid ""
"Similar to the \"!\" command, except that the command is expanded in the "
"same way as prompt strings.  For example, the name of the current file would "
"be given as \"%f\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:599
#, no-wrap
msgid "| E<lt>mE<gt> shell-command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:610
msgid ""
"E<lt>mE<gt> represents any mark letter.  Pipes a section of the input file "
"to the given shell command.  The section of the file to be piped is between "
"the position marked by the letter and the current screen.  The entire "
"current screen is included, regardless of whether the marked position is "
"before or after the current screen.  E<lt>mE<gt> may also be \\*^ or $ to "
"indicate beginning or end of file respectively.  If E<lt>mE<gt> is \\&.\\& "
"or newline, the current screen is piped.  If a \\*^P (CONTROL-P) is entered "
"immediately after the mark letter, no \"done\" message is printed after the "
"shell command is executed."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:610
#, no-wrap
msgid "s filename"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:613
msgid ""
"Save the input to a file.  This works only if the input is a pipe, not an "
"ordinary file."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:613 original/man1/lesskey.1:289
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^O\\*^O"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:626
msgid ""
"Run a shell command to open the URI in the current OSC 8 hyperlink, selected "
"by a previous \\*^O\\*^N or \\*^O\\*^P command.  To find the shell command, "
"the environment variable named \"LESS_OSC8_xxx\" is read, where \"xxx\" is "
"the scheme from the URI (the part before the first colon), or is empty if "
"there is no colon in the URI.  The value of the environment variable is then "
"expanded in the same way as prompt strings (in particular, any instance of "
"\"%o\" is replaced with the URI)  to produce an OSC 8 \"handler\" shell "
"command.  The standard output from the handler is an \"opener\" shell "
"command which is then executed to open the URI."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:628
msgid "There are two special cases:"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:629
#, no-wrap
msgid "1."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:633
msgid ""
"If the URI begins with \"#\", the remainder of the URI is taken to be the "
"value of the id parameter in another OSC 8 link in the same file, and "
"\\*^O\\*^O will simply jump to that link."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:633
#, no-wrap
msgid "2."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:639
msgid ""
"If the opener begins with the characters \":e\" followed by whitespace and a "
"filename, then instead of running the opener as a shell command, the "
"specified filename is opened in the current instance of B<less>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:643
msgid ""
"In a simple case where the opener accepts the complete URI as a command line "
"parameter, the handler may be as simple as"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:647
#, no-wrap
msgid "echo mybrowser \\*'%o\\*'\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:652
msgid ""
"In other cases, the URI may need to be modified, so the handler may have to "
"do some manipulation of the %o value."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:666
msgid ""
"If the LESS_OSC8_xxx variable is not set, the variable LESS_OSC8_ANY is "
"tried.  If neither LESS_OSC8_xxx nor LESS_OSC8_ANY is set, links using the "
"\"xxx\" scheme cannot be opened.  However, there are default handlers for "
"the schemes \"man\" (used when LESS_OSC8_man is not set)  and \"file\" (used "
"when LESS_OSC8_file is not set), which should work on systems which provide "
"the B<sed>(1)  command and a shell with syntax compatible with the Bourne "
"shell B<sh>(1).  If you use LESS_OSC8_ANY to override LESS_OSC8_file, you "
"must set LESS_OSC8_file to \"-\" to indicate that the default value should "
"not be used, and likewise for LESS_OSC8_man."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:677
msgid ""
"The URI passed to an OSC8 handler via %o is guaranteed not to contain any "
"single quote or double quote characters, but it may contain any other shell "
"metacharacters such as semicolons, dollar signs, ampersands, etc.  The "
"handler should take care to appropriately quote parameters in the opener "
"command, to prevent execution of unintended shell commands in the case of "
"opening a URI which contains shell metacharacters.  Also, since the handler "
"command is expanded like a command prompt, any metacharacters interpreted by "
"prompt expansion (such as percent, dot, colon, backslash, etc.) must be "
"escaped with a backslash (see the PROMPTS section for details)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:678
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^X"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:698
msgid ""
"When the \"Waiting for data\" message is displayed, such as while in the F "
"command, pressing \\*^X will stop B<less> from waiting and return to a "
"prompt.  This may cause B<less> to think that the file ends at the current "
"position, so it may be necessary to use the R or F command to see more "
"data.  The B<--intr> option can be used to specify a different character to "
"use instead of \\*^X.  This command works only on systems that support the "
"B<poll>(2)  function.  On systems without B<poll>(2), the interrupt "
"character (usually \\*^C) can be used instead."
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:699
#, no-wrap
msgid "OPTIONS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:704
msgid ""
"Command line options are described below.  Most options may be changed while "
"B<less> is running, via the \"-\" command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:722
msgid ""
"Some options may be given in one of two forms: either a dash followed by a "
"single letter, or two dashes followed by a long option name.  A long option "
"name may be abbreviated as long as the abbreviation is unambiguous.  For "
"example, B<--mouse> may be abbreviated B<--mou>, but not B<--mo>, since both "
"B<--mouse> and B<--modelines> begin with B<--mo>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:734
msgid ""
"Some long option names are in uppercase, such as B<--QUIT-AT-EOF>, as "
"distinct from B<--quit-at-eof>.  Such option names need only have their "
"first letter capitalized; the remainder of the name may be in either case.  "
"For example, B<--Quit-at-eof> is equivalent to B<--QUIT-AT-EOF>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:741
msgid ""
"Options are also taken from the environment variable \"LESS\".  For example, "
"to avoid typing \"less -options \\&...\\&\" each time B<less> is invoked, "
"you might tell B<csh>:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:743
msgid "setenv LESS \"-options\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:746
msgid "or if you use B<sh>:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:748
msgid "LESS=\"-options\"; export LESS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:752
msgid ""
"On MS-DOS and Windows, you don't need the quotes, but you should be careful "
"that any percent signs in the options string are not interpreted as an "
"environment variable expansion."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:759
msgid ""
"The environment variable is parsed before the command line, so command line "
"options override the LESS environment variable.  If an option appears in the "
"LESS variable, it can be reset to its default value on the command line by "
"beginning the command line option with \\[dq]B<-+>\\[dq]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:769
msgid ""
"Some options like B<-k> or B<-D> require a string to follow the option "
"letter.  The string for that option is considered to end when a dollar sign "
"($) is found.  For example, you can set two B<-D> options like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:772
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS=\"Dnwb$Dsbw\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:784
msgid ""
"If the B<--use-backslash> option appears earlier in the options, then a "
"dollar sign or backslash may be included literally in an option string by "
"preceding it with a backslash.  If the B<--use-backslash> option is not in "
"effect, then backslashes are not treated specially, and there is no way to "
"include a dollar sign in the option string."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:784
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-?> or B<--help>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:790
msgid ""
"This option displays a summary of the commands accepted by B<less> (the same "
"as the h command).  (Depending on how your shell interprets the question "
"mark, it may be necessary to quote the question mark, thus: \"B<-\\e?>\".)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:790
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-a> or B<--search-skip-screen>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:804
msgid ""
"By default, forward searches start at the top of the displayed screen and "
"backwards searches start at the bottom of the displayed screen (except for "
"repeated searches invoked by the n or N commands, which start after or "
"before the \"target\" line respectively; see the B<-j> option for more about "
"the target line).  The B<-a> option causes forward searches to instead start "
"at the bottom of the screen and backward searches to start at the top of the "
"screen, thus skipping all lines displayed on the screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:804
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-A> or B<--SEARCH-SKIP-SCREEN>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:813
msgid ""
"Causes all forward searches (not just non-repeated searches)  to start just "
"after the target line, and all backward searches to start just before the "
"target line.  Thus, forward searches will skip part of the displayed screen "
"(from the first line up to and including the target line).  Similarly "
"backwards searches will skip the displayed screen from the last line up to "
"and including the target line.  This was the default behavior in less "
"versions prior to 441."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:813
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-b>I<n> or B<--buffers=>I<n>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:827
msgid ""
"Specifies the amount of buffer space B<less> will use for each file, in "
"units of kilobytes (1024 bytes).  By default 64\\ KB of buffer space is used "
"for each file (unless the file is a pipe; see the B<-B> option).  The B<-b> "
"option specifies instead that I<n> kilobytes of buffer space should be used "
"for each file.  If I<n> is -1, buffer space is unlimited; that is, the "
"entire file can be read into memory."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:827
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-B> or B<--auto-buffers>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:846
msgid ""
"By default, when data is read from a pipe, buffers are allocated "
"automatically as needed.  If a large amount of data is read from the pipe, "
"this can cause a large amount of memory to be allocated.  The B<-B> option "
"disables this automatic allocation of buffers for pipes, so that only 64\\ "
"KB (or the amount of space specified by the B<-b> option)  is used for the "
"pipe.  Warning: use of B<-B> can result in erroneous display, since only the "
"most recently viewed part of the piped data is kept in memory; any earlier "
"data is lost.  Lost characters are displayed as question marks."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:846
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-c> or B<--clear-screen>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:850
msgid ""
"Causes full screen repaints to be painted from the top line down.  By "
"default, full screen repaints are done by scrolling from the bottom of the "
"screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:850
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-C> or B<--CLEAR-SCREEN>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:855
msgid "Same as B<-c>, for compatibility with older versions of B<less>."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:855
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-d> or B<--dumb>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:867
msgid ""
"The B<-d> option suppresses the error message normally displayed if the "
"terminal is dumb; that is, lacks some important capability, such as the "
"ability to clear the screen or scroll backward.  The B<-d> option does not "
"otherwise change the behavior of B<less> on a dumb terminal."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:867
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-Dx>I<color> or B<--color=x>I<color>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:871
msgid ""
"Changes the color of different parts of the displayed text.  B<x> is a "
"single character which selects the type of text whose color is being set:"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:872
#, no-wrap
msgid "B"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:874
msgid "Binary characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:874
#, no-wrap
msgid "C"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:876
msgid "Control characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:876 original/man1/lesskey.1:280
#, no-wrap
msgid "E"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:878
msgid "Errors and informational messages."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:878 original/man1/lesskey.1:326
#, no-wrap
msgid "H"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:882
msgid "Header lines and columns, set via the B<--header> option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:884
msgid "Mark letters in the status column."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:888
msgid "Line numbers enabled via the B<-N> option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:890
msgid "Prompts."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:892
msgid "The rscroll character."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:892
#, no-wrap
msgid "S"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:894
msgid "Search results."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:894
#, no-wrap
msgid "W"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:898
msgid "The highlight enabled via the B<-w> option."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:898
#, no-wrap
msgid "1-5"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:905
msgid ""
"The text in a search result which matches the first through fifth "
"parenthesized sub-pattern.  Sub-pattern coloring works only if B<less> is "
"built with one of the regular expression libraries B<posix>, B<pcre>, or "
"B<pcre2>."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:905 original/man1/less.1:2526
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:201
#, no-wrap
msgid "d"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:907
msgid "Bold text."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:907 original/man1/less.1:955
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:192
#, no-wrap
msgid "k"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:909
msgid "Blinking text."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:909 original/man1/lesskey.1:299
#, no-wrap
msgid "s"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:911
msgid "Standout text."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:911 original/man1/lesskey.1:203
#, no-wrap
msgid "u"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:913
msgid "Underlined text."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:933
msgid ""
"The uppercase letters and digits can be used only when the B<--use-color> "
"option is enabled.  When text color is specified by both an uppercase letter "
"and a lowercase letter, the uppercase letter takes precedence.  For example, "
"error messages are normally displayed as standout text.  So if both \"s\" "
"and \"E\" are given a color, the \"E\" color applies to error messages, and "
"the \"s\" color applies to other standout text.  The lowercase letters refer "
"to bold and underline text formed by overstriking with backspaces (see the "
"B<-U> option) and to non-content text (such as line numbers and prompts), "
"but not to text formatted using ANSI escape sequences with the B<-R> option "
"(but see the note below for different behavior on Windows and MS-DOS)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:943
msgid ""
"A lowercase letter may be followed by a + to indicate that the normal format "
"change and the specified color should both be used.  For example, B<-Dug> "
"displays underlined text as green without underlining; the green color has "
"replaced the usual underline formatting.  But B<-Du+g> displays underlined "
"text as both green and in underlined format."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:945
msgid "I<color> is either a 4-bit color string or an 8-bit color string:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:949
msgid ""
"A 4-bit color string is one or two characters, where the first character "
"specifies the foreground color and the second specifies the background color "
"as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:949 original/man1/less.1:2522
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:210
#, no-wrap
msgid "b"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:951
msgid "Blue"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:951 original/man1/less.1:2524
#, no-wrap
msgid "c"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:953
msgid "Cyan"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:953 original/man1/lesskey.1:229
#, no-wrap
msgid "g"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:955
msgid "Green"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:957
msgid "Black"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:959
msgid "Magenta"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:959 original/man1/lesskey.1:224
#, no-wrap
msgid "r"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:961
msgid "Red"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:963
msgid "White"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:963 original/man1/lesskey.1:193
#, no-wrap
msgid "y"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:965
msgid "Yellow"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:976
msgid ""
"The corresponding uppercase letter denotes a brighter shade of the color.  "
"For example, B<-DNGk> displays line numbers as bright green text on a black "
"background, and B<-DEbR> displays error messages as blue text on a bright "
"red background.  If either character is a \"-\" or is omitted, the "
"corresponding color is set to that of normal text."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:982
msgid ""
"An 8-bit color string is one or two decimal integers separated by a dot, "
"where the first integer specifies the foreground color and the second "
"specifies the background color.  Each integer is a value between 0 and 255 "
"inclusive which selects a \"CSI 38;5\" color value (see"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:984
msgid "https://\\*:en\\*:.wikipedia\\*:.org/\\*:wiki/\\*:ANSI_escape_code\\*:#SGR)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:987
msgid ""
"If either integer is a \"-\" or is omitted, the corresponding color is set "
"to that of normal text."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:990
msgid ""
"A 4-bit or 8-bit color string may be followed by one or more of the "
"following characters to set text attributes in addition to the color."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:990
#, no-wrap
msgid "s or ~"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:992
msgid "Standout (reverse video)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:992
#, no-wrap
msgid "u or _"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:994
msgid "Underline"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:994
#, no-wrap
msgid "d or *"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:996
msgid "Bold"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:996
#, no-wrap
msgid "l or &"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:998
msgid "Blinking"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1003
msgid ""
"On MS-DOS and Windows, the B<--color> option behaves differently from what "
"is described above in these ways:"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1003 original/man1/less.1:1006
#: original/man1/less.1:1012 original/man1/less.1:1028
#: original/man1/less.1:1031 original/man1/less.1:1034
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\(bu"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1006
msgid ""
"The bold (d and *) and blinking (l and &) text attributes at the end of a "
"color string are not supported."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1012
msgid ""
"Lowercase color selector letters refer to text formatted by ANSI escape "
"sequences with B<-R>, in addition to overstruck and non-content text (but "
"see B<-Da>)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1017
msgid ""
"For historical reasons, when a lowercase color selector letter is followed "
"by a numeric color value, the number is not interpreted as an \"CSI 38;5\" "
"color value as described above, but instead as a 4-bit"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1019
msgid "CHAR_INFO.Attributes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1022
msgid "value, between 0 and 15 inclusive (see"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1024
msgid "https://\\*:learn\\*:.microsoft\\*:.com/\\*:en-us/\\*:windows/\\*:console/\\*:char-info-str)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1028
msgid ""
"To avoid confusion, it is recommended that the equivalent letters rather "
"than numbers be used after a lowercase color selector on MS-DOS/Windows."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1031
msgid ""
"Numeric color values (\"CSI 38;5\" color) following an uppercase color "
"selector letter are not supported on systems earlier than Windows 10."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1034
msgid ""
"Only a limited set of ANSI escape sequences to set color in the content work "
"correctly.  4-bit color sequences work, but \"CSI 38;5\" color sequences do "
"not."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1046
msgid ""
"The B<-Da> option makes the behavior of B<--color> more similar to its "
"behavior on non-MS-DOS/Windows systems by (1)  making lowercase color "
"selector letters not affect text formatted with ANSI escape sequences, and "
"(2)  allowing \"CSI 38;5\" color sequences in the content work by passing "
"them to the terminal (only on Windows 10 and later; on earlier Windows "
"systems, such sequences do not work regardless of the setting of B<-Da>)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1047
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-e> or B<--quit-at-eof>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1055
msgid ""
"Causes B<less> to automatically exit the second time it reaches "
"end-of-file.  By default, the only way to exit B<less> is via the \"q\" "
"command."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1055
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-E> or B<--QUIT-AT-EOF>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1059
msgid "Causes B<less> to automatically exit the first time it reaches end-of-file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1059
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-f> or B<--force>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1070
msgid ""
"Forces non-regular files to be opened.  (A non-regular file is a directory "
"or a device special file.)  Also suppresses the warning message when a "
"binary file is opened.  By default, B<less> will refuse to open non-regular "
"files.  Note that some operating systems will not allow directories to be "
"read, even if B<-f> is set."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1070
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-F> or B<--quit-if-one-screen>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1076
msgid ""
"Causes B<less> to automatically exit if the entire file can be displayed on "
"the first screen.  Also see the description of the LESS_SHELL_LINES "
"environment variable below."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1076
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-g> or B<--hilite-search>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1087
msgid ""
"Normally, B<less> will highlight ALL strings which match the last search "
"command.  The B<-g> option changes this behavior to highlight only the "
"particular string which was found by the last search command.  This can "
"cause B<less> to run somewhat faster than the default."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1087
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-G> or B<--HILITE-SEARCH>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1089
msgid ""
"The -G option suppresses all highlighting of strings found by search "
"commands."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1089
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-h>I<n> or B<--max-back-scroll=>I<n>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1097
msgid ""
"Specifies a maximum number of lines to scroll backward.  If it is necessary "
"to scroll backward more than I<n> lines, the screen is repainted in a "
"forward direction instead.  (If the terminal does not have the ability to "
"scroll backward, B<-h0> is implied.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1097
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-i> or B<--ignore-case>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1104
msgid ""
"Causes searches to ignore case; that is, uppercase and lowercase are "
"considered identical.  This option is ignored if any uppercase letters "
"appear in the search pattern; in other words, if a pattern contains "
"uppercase letters, then that search does not ignore case."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1104
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-I> or B<--IGNORE-CASE>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1109
msgid ""
"Like B<-i>, but searches ignore case even if the pattern contains uppercase "
"letters."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1109
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-j>I<n> or B<--jump-target=>I<n>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1131
msgid ""
"Specifies a line on the screen where the \"target\" line is to be "
"positioned.  The target line is the line specified by any command to search "
"for a pattern, jump to a line number, jump to a file percentage or jump to a "
"tag.  The screen line may be specified by a number: the top line on the "
"screen is 1, the next is 2, and so on.  The number may be negative to "
"specify a line relative to the bottom of the screen: the bottom line on the "
"screen is -1, the second to the bottom is -2, and so on.  Alternately, the "
"screen line may be specified as a fraction of the height of the screen, "
"starting with a decimal point: \\&.5 is in the middle of the screen, \\&.3 "
"is three tenths down from the first line, and so on.  If the line is "
"specified as a fraction, the actual line number is recalculated if the "
"terminal window is resized.  If the B<--header> option is used and the "
"target line specified by B<-j> would be obscured by the header, the target "
"line is moved to the first line after the header."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1150
msgid ""
"If any form of the B<-j> option is used, repeated forward searches (invoked "
"with \"n\" or \"N\")  begin at the line immediately after the target line, "
"and repeated backward searches begin at the target line, unless changed by "
"B<-a> or B<-A>.  For example, if \\[dq]B<-j4>\\[dq] is used, the target line "
"is the fourth line on the screen, so forward searches begin at the fifth "
"line on the screen.  However nonrepeated searches (invoked with \"/\" or "
"\"?\")  always begin at the first or last line on the screen respectively."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1151
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-J> or B<--status-column>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1154
msgid ""
"Displays a status column at the left edge of the screen.  The character "
"displayed in the status column may be one of:"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:1155 original/man1/lesskey.1:260
#, no-wrap
msgid "E<gt>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1161
msgid ""
"The line is chopped with the B<-S> option, and the text that is chopped off "
"beyond the right edge of the screen contains a match for the current search."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:1161 original/man1/lesskey.1:236
#, no-wrap
msgid "E<lt>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1165
msgid ""
"The line is horizontally shifted, and the text that is shifted beyond the "
"left side of the screen contains a match for the current search."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1165
#, no-wrap
msgid "="
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1168
msgid ""
"The line is both chopped and shifted, and there are matches beyond both "
"sides of the screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1168 original/man1/less.1:1657
#, no-wrap
msgid "*"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1171
msgid ""
"There are matches in the visible part of the line but none to the right or "
"left of it."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1171
#, no-wrap
msgid "a-z, A-Z"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1173
msgid ""
"The line has been marked with the corresponding letter via the m or M "
"command."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:1173 original/man1/lesskey.1:307
#, no-wrap
msgid "#"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1178
msgid ""
"The line has been marked by left-clicking it with the mouse when the "
"B<--mouse> option is in effect."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1179
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-k>I<filename> or B<--lesskey-file=>I<filename>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1196
msgid ""
"Causes B<less> to open and interpret the named file as a B<lesskey>(1)  "
"binary file.  Multiple B<-k> options may be specified.  If the LESSKEY or "
"LESSKEY_SYSTEM environment variable is set, or if a lesskey file is found in "
"a standard place (see KEY BINDINGS), it is also used as a B<lesskey> file.  "
"Note the warning under B<--lesskey-content> below."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1196
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--lesskey-src=>I<filename>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1221
msgid ""
"Causes B<less> to open and interpret the named file as a B<lesskey>(1)  "
"source file.  If the LESSKEYIN or LESSKEYIN_SYSTEM environment variable is "
"set, or if a lesskey source file is found in a standard place (see KEY "
"BINDINGS), it is also used as a lesskey source file.  Prior to version 582, "
"the B<lesskey> program needed to be run to convert a lesskey I<source> file "
"to a lesskey I<binary> file for B<less> to use.  Newer versions of B<less> "
"read the lesskey source file directly and ignore the binary file if the "
"source file exists.  Note the warning under B<--lesskey-content> below."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1221
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--lesskey-content=>I<text>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1231
msgid ""
"Causes B<less> to interpret the specified text as the contents of a "
"B<lesskey>(1)  source file.  In the text, B<lesskey> lines may be separated "
"by either newlines as usual, or by semicolons.  A literal semicolon may be "
"represented by a backslash followed by a semicolon."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1243
msgid ""
"Warning: certain environment variables such as LESS, LESSSECURE, LESSCHARSET "
"and others, which are used early in startup, cannot be set in a file "
"specified by a command line option (B<--lesskey>,B<--lesskey-src> or "
"B<--lesskey-content>).  When using a B<lesskey> file to set environment "
"variables, it is safer to use the default lesskey file, or to specify the "
"file using the LESSKEYIN or LESSKEY_CONTENT environment variables rather "
"than using a command line option."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1243
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-K> or B<--quit-on-intr>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1251
msgid ""
"Causes B<less> to exit immediately (with status 2)  when an interrupt "
"character (usually \\*^C) is typed.  Normally, an interrupt character causes "
"B<less> to stop whatever it is doing and return to its command prompt."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1251
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-L> or B<--no-lessopen>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1258
msgid ""
"Ignore the LESSOPEN environment variable (see the INPUT PREPROCESSOR section "
"below).  This option can be set from within B<less>, but it will apply only "
"to files opened subsequently, not to the file which is currently open."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1258
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-m> or B<--long-prompt>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1267
msgid ""
"Causes B<less> to prompt verbosely (like B<more>(1)), with the percent into "
"the file.  By default, B<less> prompts with a colon."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1267
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-M> or B<--LONG-PROMPT>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1272
msgid "Causes B<less> to prompt even more verbosely than B<more>(1)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1272
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-n> or B<--line-numbers>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1281
msgid ""
"Suppresses line numbers.  The default (to use line numbers) may cause "
"B<less> to run more slowly in some cases, especially with a very large input "
"file.  Using line numbers means: the line number will be displayed in the "
"verbose prompt and in the = command, and the v command will pass the current "
"line number to the editor (see also the discussion of LESSEDIT in PROMPTS "
"below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1281
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-N> or B<--LINE-NUMBERS>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1284
msgid ""
"Causes a line number to be displayed at the beginning of each line in the "
"display."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1284
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-o>I<filename> or B<--log-file=>I<filename>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1293
msgid ""
"Causes B<less> to copy its input to the named file as it is being viewed.  "
"This applies only when the input file is a pipe, not an ordinary file.  If "
"the file already exists, B<less> will ask for confirmation before "
"overwriting it."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1293
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-O>I<filename> or B<--LOG-FILE=>I<filename>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1300
msgid ""
"The B<-O> option is like B<-o,> but it will overwrite an existing file "
"without asking for confirmation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1314
msgid ""
"If no log file has been specified, the B<-o> and B<-O> options can be used "
"from within B<less> to specify a log file.  Without a file name, they will "
"simply report the name of the log file.  The \"s\" command is equivalent to "
"specifying B<-o> from within B<less>."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1314
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-p>I<pattern> or B<--pattern=>I<pattern>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1320
msgid ""
"The -p option on the command line is equivalent to specifying +/I<pattern>; "
"that is, it tells B<less> to start at the first occurrence of I<pattern> in "
"the file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1320
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-P>I<prompt> or B<--prompt=>I<prompt>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1329
msgid ""
"Provides a way to tailor the three prompt styles to your own preference.  "
"This option would normally be put in the LESS environment variable, rather "
"than being typed in with each B<less> command.  Such an option must either "
"be the last option in the LESS variable, or be terminated by a dollar sign."
msgstr ""

#. type: TP
#: original/man1/less.1:1331
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-Ps>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1335
msgid "followed by a string changes the default (short) prompt to that string."
msgstr ""

#. type: TP
#: original/man1/less.1:1335
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-Pm>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1340
msgid "changes the medium (B<-m>)  prompt."
msgstr ""

#. type: TP
#: original/man1/less.1:1340
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-PM>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1345
msgid "changes the long (B<-M>)  prompt."
msgstr ""

#. type: TP
#: original/man1/less.1:1345
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-Ph>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1348
msgid "changes the prompt for the help screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: TP
#: original/man1/less.1:1348
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-P=>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1351
msgid "changes the message printed by the = command."
msgstr ""

#. type: TP
#: original/man1/less.1:1351
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-Pw>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1354
msgid "changes the message printed while waiting for data (in the \"F\" command)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1359
msgid ""
"All prompt strings consist of a sequence of letters and special escape "
"sequences.  See the section on PROMPTS for more details."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1359
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-q> or B<--quiet> or B<--silent>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1368
msgid ""
"Causes moderately \"quiet\" operation: the terminal bell is not rung if an "
"attempt is made to scroll past the end of the file or before the beginning "
"of the file.  If the terminal has a \"visual bell\", it is used instead.  "
"The bell will be rung on certain other errors, such as typing an invalid "
"character.  The default is to ring the terminal bell in all such cases."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1368
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-Q> or B<--QUIET> or B<--SILENT>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1373
msgid ""
"Causes totally \"quiet\" operation: the terminal bell is never rung.  If the "
"terminal has a \"visual bell\", it is used in all cases where the terminal "
"bell would have been rung."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1373
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-r> or B<--raw-control-chars>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1389
msgid ""
"Causes \"raw\" control characters to be displayed.  The default is to "
"display control characters using the caret notation; for example, a "
"control-A (octal 001) is displayed as \"\\*^A\" (with some exceptions as "
"described under the B<-U> option).  Warning: when the B<-r> option is used, "
"B<less> cannot keep track of the actual appearance of the screen (since this "
"depends on how the screen responds to each type of control character).  "
"Thus, various display problems may result, such as long lines being split in "
"the wrong place."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1393
msgid "USE OF THE B<-r> OPTION IS DANGEROUS AND IS NOT RECOMMENDED."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1402
msgid ""
"The B<-r> option can be set on the command line or via the - command, but to "
"avoid unintentional use, it cannot be set in a LESS environment variable.  "
"If B<-r> appears in a LESS environment variable, it is treated as if it were "
"B<-R>."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1402
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-R> or B<--RAW-CONTROL-CHARS>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1411
msgid ""
"Like B<-r>, but only a limited set of escape sequences are output in \"raw\" "
"form.  Unlike B<-r>, the screen appearance is maintained correctly.  The "
"sequences which are output raw are:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1413
msgid "1. ANSI SGR (\"color\") sequences"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1415
msgid "2. OSC 8 hyperlinks"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1418
msgid ""
"3. Other OSC sequences, if the OSC type number is listed in the "
"LESSANSIOSCALLOW environment variable"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1422
msgid ""
"4. OSC sequences starting with a non-standard introductory character (that "
"is, something other than \"]\"), if the character is listed in the "
"LESSANSIOSCCHARS environment variable followed by an asterisk"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1424
msgid "ANSI color escape sequences are sequences of the form:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1427
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tESC [ \\&...\\& m\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1434
msgid ""
"where the \"...\\&\" is zero or more color specification characters.  Color "
"escape sequences are only supported when the color is changed within one "
"line, not across lines.  In other words, the beginning of each line is "
"assumed to be normal (non-colored), regardless of any escape sequences in "
"previous lines."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1445
msgid ""
"You can make B<less> think that characters other than \"m\" can end ANSI "
"color escape sequences by setting the environment variable LESSANSIENDCHARS "
"to the list of characters which can end a color escape sequence.  And you "
"can make B<less> think that characters other than the standard ones may "
"appear between the ESC and the m by setting the environment variable "
"LESSANSIMIDCHARS to the list of characters which can appear."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1447
msgid "OSC sequences are of the form:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1450
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tESC ] N ; \\&...\\& \\e7\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1455
msgid ""
"where the OSC type number N is a decimal integer.  The terminating sequence "
"may be either a BEL character (\\e7)  as above, or the two-character "
"sequence \"ESC \\e\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1455
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-s> or B<--squeeze-blank-lines>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1460
msgid ""
"Causes consecutive blank lines to be squeezed into a single blank line.  "
"This is useful when viewing B<nroff>(1)  output."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1460
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-S> or B<--chop-long-lines>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1476
msgid ""
"Causes lines longer than the screen width to be chopped (truncated) rather "
"than wrapped.  That is, the portion of a long line that does not fit in the "
"screen width is not displayed until you press RIGHT-ARROW.  The default is "
"to wrap long lines; that is, display the remainder on the next line.  See "
"also the B<--wordwrap> option.  While the B<--header> option is active, the "
"B<-S> option is ignored, and lines longer than the screen width are "
"truncated."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1476
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-t>I<tag> or B<--tag=>I<tag>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1491
msgid ""
"The B<-t> option, followed immediately by a TAG, will edit the file "
"containing that tag.  For this to work, tag information must be available; "
"for example, there may be a file in the current directory called \"tags\", "
"which was previously built by B<ctags>(1)  or an equivalent command.  If the "
"environment variable LESSGLOBALTAGS is set, it is taken to be the name of a "
"command compatible with B<global>(1), and that command is executed to find "
"the tag.  (See"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1493
msgid "http://\\*:www\\*:.gnu\\*:.org/\\*:software/\\*:global/\\*:global\\*:.html)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1503
msgid ""
"The B<-t> option may also be specified from within B<less> (using the - "
"command) as a way of examining a new file.  The command \":t\" is equivalent "
"to specifying B<-t> from within B<less>."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1503
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-T>I<tagsfile> or B<--tag-file=>I<tagsfile>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1505
msgid "Specifies a tags file to be used instead of \"tags\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1505
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-u> or B<--underline-special>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1508
msgid ""
"Causes backspaces and carriage returns to be treated as printable "
"characters; that is, they are sent to the terminal when they appear in the "
"input."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1508
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-U> or B<--UNDERLINE-SPECIAL>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1514
msgid ""
"Causes backspaces, tabs, carriage returns and \"formatting characters\" (as "
"defined by Unicode) to be treated as control characters; that is, they are "
"handled as specified by the B<-r> option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1541
msgid ""
"By default, if neither B<-u> nor B<-U> is given, backspaces which appear "
"adjacent to an underscore character are treated specially: the underlined "
"text is displayed using the terminal's hardware underlining capability.  "
"Also, backspaces which appear between two identical characters are treated "
"specially: the overstruck text is printed using the terminal's hardware "
"boldface capability.  Other backspaces are deleted, along with the preceding "
"character.  Carriage returns immediately followed by a newline are deleted.  "
"Other carriage returns are handled as specified by the B<-r> option.  "
"Unicode formatting characters, such as the Byte Order Mark, are sent to the "
"terminal.  Text which is overstruck or underlined can be searched for if "
"neither B<-u> nor B<-U> is in effect."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1545
msgid ""
"See also the B<--proc-backspace>,B<--proc-tab>, and B<--proc-return> "
"options."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1545
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-V> or B<--version>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1548
msgid "Displays the version number of B<less>."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1548
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-w> or B<--hilite-unread>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1564
msgid ""
"Temporarily highlights the first \"new\" line after a forward movement of a "
"full page.  The first \"new\" line is the line immediately following the "
"line previously at the bottom of the screen.  Also highlights the target "
"line after a g or p command.  The highlight is removed at the next command "
"which causes movement.  If the B<--status-line> option is in effect, the "
"entire line (the width of the screen) is highlighted.  Otherwise, only the "
"text in the line is highlighted, unless the B<-J> option is in effect, in "
"which case only the status column is highlighted."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1564
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-W> or B<--HILITE-UNREAD>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1569
msgid ""
"Like B<-w>, but temporarily highlights the first new line after any forward "
"movement command larger than one line."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1569
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-x>I<n>,...\\& or B<--tabs=>I<n>,..."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1579
msgid ""
"Sets tab stops.  If only one I<n> is specified, tab stops are set at "
"multiples of I<n>.  If multiple values separated by commas are specified, "
"tab stops are set at those positions, and then continue with the same "
"spacing as the last two.  For example, \\[dq]B<-x9,17>\\[dq] will set tabs "
"at positions 9, 17, 25, 33, etc.  The default for I<n> is 8."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1579
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-X> or B<--no-init>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1588
msgid ""
"Disables sending the termcap initialization and deinitialization strings to "
"the terminal.  This is sometimes desirable if initialization or "
"deinitialization does something unnecessary, like clearing the screen.  Note "
"that some terminals require the initialization string for proper operation, "
"so they may not behave completely correctly when B<-X> is used."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1588
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-y>I<n> or B<--max-forw-scroll=>I<n>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1599
msgid ""
"Specifies a maximum number of lines to scroll forward.  If it is necessary "
"to scroll forward more than I<n> lines, the screen is repainted instead.  "
"The B<-c> or B<-C> option may be used to repaint from the top of the screen "
"if desired.  By default, any forward movement causes scrolling."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1599
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-z>I<n> or B<--window=>I<n> or -I<n>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1615
msgid ""
"Changes the default scrolling window size to I<n> lines.  The default is one "
"screenful.  The z and w commands can also be used to change the window "
"size.  The \"z\" may be omitted for compatibility with some versions of "
"B<more>(1).  If the number I<n> is negative, it indicates I<n> lines less "
"than the current screen size.  For example, if the screen is 24 lines, "
"B<-z-4> sets the scrolling window to 20 lines.  If the screen is later "
"resized to 40 lines, the scrolling window automatically changes to 36 lines."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1615
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-\">I<cc>\\ or\\ B<--quotes=>I<cc>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1629
msgid ""
"Changes the filename quoting character.  This may be necessary if you are "
"trying to name a file which contains both spaces and quote characters.  "
"Followed by a single character, this changes the quote character to that "
"character.  Filenames containing a space should then be surrounded by that "
"character rather than by double quotes.  Followed by two characters, changes "
"the open quote to the first character, and the close quote to the second "
"character.  Filenames containing a space should then be preceded by the open "
"quote character and followed by the close quote character.  Note that even "
"after the quote characters are changed, this option remains -\" (a dash "
"followed by a double quote)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1629
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-\\*~> or B<--tilde>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1632
msgid ""
"Normally lines after end of file are displayed as a single tilde (\\*~).  "
"This option causes lines after end of file to be displayed as blank lines."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1632
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-#> or B<--shift>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1642
msgid ""
"Specifies the default number of positions to scroll horizontally in the "
"RIGHTARROW and LEFTARROW commands.  If the number specified is zero, it sets "
"the default number of positions to one half of the screen width.  "
"Alternately, the number may be specified as a fraction of the width of the "
"screen, starting with a decimal point: \\&.5 is half of the screen width, "
"\\&.3 is three tenths of the screen width, and so on.  If the number is "
"specified as a fraction, the actual number of scroll positions is "
"recalculated if the terminal window is resized."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1642
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--autosave=>I<actions>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1648
msgid ""
"Normally the history file is saved only when B<less> exits.  This option "
"specifies other actions which will cause the history file to be saved.  Each "
"action is defined by a single character in the I<actions> string:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1653
msgid "Setting or clearing a mark while B<--save-marks> is in effect."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:1653 original/man1/lesskey.1:266
#, no-wrap
msgid "/"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1655
msgid "Searching."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:1655 original/man1/lesskey.1:306
#, no-wrap
msgid "!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1657
msgid "Running a shell command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1659
msgid "Any action; same as \"m/!\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1666
msgid ""
"Can be set to \"-\" to specify the default, that only exiting B<less> will "
"cause the history file to be saved.  Note that, depending on your shell, if "
"you specify this option on the command line, the \"!\" and \"*\" characters "
"may need to be escaped or quoted."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1666
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--cmd=>I<commands>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1682
msgid ""
"The specified string is taken to be an initial command to B<less>.  This is "
"similar to specifying \"+I<commands>\", except that commands specified by "
"B<--cmd> are not executed if B<less> exits immediately due to the use of the "
"B<-E> or B<-F> option, while commands specified by the B<+> option are "
"executed even if B<less> exits immediately."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1682
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--exit-follow-on-close>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1687
msgid ""
"When using the \"F\" command on a pipe, B<less> will automatically stop "
"waiting for more data when the input side of the pipe is closed."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1687
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--file-size>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1697
msgid ""
"If B<--file-size> is specified, B<less> will determine the size of the file "
"immediately after opening the file.  Then the \"=\" command will display the "
"number of lines in the file.  Normally this is not done, because it can be "
"slow if the input file is non-seekable (such as a pipe) and is large."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1697
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--follow-name>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1712
msgid ""
"Normally, if the input file is renamed while an F command is executing, "
"B<less> will continue to display the contents of the original file despite "
"its name change.  If B<--follow-name> is specified, during an F command "
"B<less> will periodically attempt to reopen the file by name.  If the reopen "
"succeeds and the file is a different file from the original (which means "
"that a new file has been created with the same name as the original (now "
"renamed) file), B<less> will display the contents of that new file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1712
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--form-feed>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1716
msgid ""
"When scrolling forward or backward in the file, stop if a line beginning "
"with a form feed character (\\*^L) is reached.  This can be useful when "
"viewing a file which uses form feeds between pages."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1716
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--header=>I<L>,I<C>,I<N>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1740
msgid ""
"Sets the number of header lines and columns displayed on the screen.  The "
"number of header lines is set to I<L>.  If I<L> is 0, header lines are "
"disabled.  If I<L> is empty or missing, the number of header lines is "
"unchanged.  The number of header columns is set to I<C>.  If I<C> is 0, "
"header columns are disabled.  If I<C> is empty or missing, the number of "
"header columns is unchanged.  The first header line is set to line number "
"I<N> in the file.  If I<N> is empty or missing, it is taken to be the number "
"of the line currently displayed in the first line of the screen (if the "
"B<--header> command has been issued from within B<less>), or 1 (if the "
"B<--header> option has been given on the command line).  The special form "
"\\[dq]B<--header=->\\[dq] disables header lines and header columns, and is "
"equivalent to \\[dq]B<--header=0,0>\\[dq]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1748
msgid ""
"When I<L> is nonzero, the first I<L> lines at the top of the screen are "
"replaced with the I<L> lines of the file beginning at line I<N>, regardless "
"of what part of the file is being viewed.  When header lines are displayed, "
"any file contents before the header line cannot be viewed.  When I<C> is "
"nonzero, the first I<C> characters displayed at the beginning of each line "
"are replaced with the first I<C> characters of the line, even if the rest of "
"the line is scrolled horizontally."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1756
msgid ""
"While the B<--header> option is active, lines longer than the screen width "
"are truncated, and the B<-S> option is ignored."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1757
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--incsearch>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1762
msgid ""
"Subsequent search commands will be \"incremental\"; that is, B<less> will "
"advance to the next line containing the search pattern as each character of "
"the pattern is typed in."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1762
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--intr=>I<c>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1769
msgid ""
"Use the character I<c> instead of \\*^X to interrupt a read when the "
"\"Waiting for data\" message is displayed.  I<c> must be an ASCII character; "
"that is, one with a value between 1 and 127 inclusive.  A caret followed by "
"a single character can be used to specify a control character."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1769
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--line-num-width=>I<n>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1773
msgid ""
"Sets the minimum width of the line number field when the -N option is in "
"effect to I<n> characters.  The default is 7."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1773
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--match-shift=>I<n>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1784
msgid ""
"When B<-S> is in effect, if a search match is not visible because it is "
"shifted to the left or right of the currently visible screen, the text will "
"horizontally shift to ensure that the search match is visible.  This option "
"selects the column in which the first character of the search match will be "
"placed after the shift.  In other words, there will be I<n> characters "
"visible to the left of the search match."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1790
msgid ""
"Alternately, the number may be specified as a fraction of the width of the "
"screen, starting with a decimal point: \\&.5 is half of the screen width, "
"\\&.3 is three tenths of the screen width, and so on.  If the number is "
"specified as a fraction, the actual number of scroll positions is "
"recalculated if the terminal window is resized."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1790
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--modelines=>I<n>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1801
msgid ""
"Before displaying a file, B<less> will read the first I<n> lines to try to "
"find a vim-compatible I<modeline>.  If I<n> is zero, B<less> does not try to "
"find modelines.  By using a modeline, the file itself can specify the tab "
"stops that should be used when viewing it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1820
msgid ""
"A modeline contains, anywhere in the line, a program name (\"vi\", \"vim\", "
"\"ex\", or \"less\"), followed by a colon, possibly followed by the word "
"\"set\", and finally followed by zero or more option settings.  If the word "
"\"set\" is used, option settings are separated by spaces, and end at the "
"first colon.  If the word \"set\" is not used, option settings may be "
"separated by either spaces or colons.  The word \"set\" is required if the "
"program name is \"less\" but optional if any of the other three names are "
"used.  If any option setting is of the form \"tabstop=I<n>\" or \"ts=I<n>\", "
"then tab stops are automatically set as if B<--tabs=>I<n> had been given.  "
"See the B<--tabs> description for acceptable values of I<n>."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1821
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--mouse>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1838
msgid ""
"Enables mouse input: scrolling the mouse wheel down moves forward in the "
"file, scrolling the mouse wheel up moves backwards in the file, left-click "
"sets the \"#\" mark to the line where the mouse is clicked, and right-click "
"(or any other) returns to the \"#\" mark position.  Holding down the left "
"button and dragging also moves in the file.  If a left-click is performed "
"with the mouse cursor on an OSC 8 hyperlink, the hyperlink is selected as if "
"by the \\*^O\\*^N command.  If a left-click is performed with the mouse "
"cursor on an OSC 8 hyperlink which is already selected, the hyperlink is "
"opened as if by the \\*^O\\*^O command.  The number of lines to scroll when "
"the wheel is moved can be set by the B<--wheel-lines> option.  Mouse input "
"works only on terminals which support X11 mouse reporting, and on Windows."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1838
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--MOUSE>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1843
msgid ""
"Like B<--mouse>, except the direction scrolled on mouse wheel movement is "
"reversed."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1843
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--no-edit-warn>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1847
msgid ""
"Don't print a warning message when using the v command on a file which was "
"opened using a LESSOPEN preprocessor (see the INPUT PREPROCESSOR section "
"below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1847
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--no-keypad>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1852
msgid ""
"Disables sending the keypad initialization and deinitialization strings to "
"the terminal.  This is sometimes useful if the keypad strings make the "
"numeric keypad behave in an undesirable manner."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1852
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--no-histdups>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1858
msgid ""
"This option changes the behavior so that if a search string or file name is "
"typed in, and the same string is already in the history list, the existing "
"copy is removed from the history list before the new one is added.  Thus, a "
"given string will appear only once in the history list.  Normally, a string "
"may appear multiple times."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1858
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--no-number-headers>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1863
msgid ""
"Header lines (defined via the B<--header> option) are not assigned line "
"numbers.  Line number 1 is assigned to the first line after any header "
"lines."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1863
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--no-paste>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1872
msgid ""
"If the terminal supports B<xterm>-compatible \"bracketed paste\", any text "
"pasted into B<less> is ignored, except that one line of text may be pasted "
"into the command line at the bottom of the screen (search strings, file "
"names, etc).  That is, the first newline of text pasted into the command "
"line and any text that follows it is ignored."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1872
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--no-search-header-lines>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1874
msgid "Searches do not include header lines, but still include header columns."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1874
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--no-search-header-columns>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1876
msgid "Searches do not include header columns, but still include header lines."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1876
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--no-search-headers>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1878
msgid "Searches do not include header lines or header columns."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1878
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--no-vbell>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1880
msgid "Disables the terminal's visual bell."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1880
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--proc-backspace>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1901
msgid ""
"If set, backspaces are handled as if neither the B<-u> option nor the B<-U> "
"option were set.  That is, a backspace adjacent to an underscore causes text "
"to be displayed in underline mode, and a backspace between identical "
"characters cause text to be displayed in boldface mode.  This option "
"overrides the B<-u> and B<-U> options, so that display of backspaces can be "
"controlled separate from tabs and carriage returns.  If not set, backspace "
"display is controlled by the B<-u> and B<-U> options."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1901
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--PROC-BACKSPACE>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1906
msgid ""
"If set, backspaces are handled as if the B<-U> option were set; that is "
"backspaces are treated as control characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1906
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--proc-return>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1925
msgid ""
"If set, carriage returns are handled as if neither the B<-u> option nor the "
"B<-U> option were set.  That is, a carriage return immediately before a "
"newline is deleted.  This option overrides the B<-u> and B<-U> options, so "
"that display of carriage returns can be controlled separate from that of "
"backspaces and tabs.  If not set, carriage return display is controlled by "
"the B<-u> and B<-U> options."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1925
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--PROC-RETURN>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1930
msgid ""
"If set, carriage returns are handled as if the B<-U> option were set; that "
"is carriage returns are treated as control characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1930
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--proc-tab>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1942
msgid ""
"If set, tabs are handled as if the B<-U> option were not set.  That is, tabs "
"are expanded to spaces.  This option overrides the B<-U> option, so that "
"display of tabs can be controlled separate from that of backspaces and "
"carriage returns.  If not set, tab display is controlled by the B<-U> "
"option."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1942
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--PROC-TAB>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1947
msgid ""
"If set, tabs are handled as if the B<-U> option were set; that is tabs are "
"treated as control characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1947
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--redraw-on-quit>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1955
msgid ""
"When quitting, after sending the terminal deinitialization string, redraws "
"the entire last screen.  On terminals whose terminal deinitialization string "
"causes the terminal to switch from an alternate screen, this makes the last "
"screenful of the current file remain visible after B<less> has quit."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1955
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--rscroll=>I<c>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1960
msgid ""
"This option changes the character used to mark truncated lines.  It may "
"begin with a two-character attribute indicator like LESSBINFMT does.  If "
"there is no attribute indicator, standout is used.  If set to \"-\", "
"truncated lines are not marked."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1960
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--save-marks>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1964
msgid ""
"Save marks in the history file, so marks are retained across different "
"invocations of B<less>."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1964
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--search-options=>I<...>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1978
msgid ""
"Sets default search modifiers.  The value is a string of one or more of the "
"characters E, F, K, N, R or W.  Setting any of these has the same effect as "
"typing that control character at the beginning of every search pattern.  For "
"example, setting B<--search-options=>I<W> is the same as typing \\*^W at the "
"beginning of every pattern.  The value may also contain a digit between 1 "
"and 5, which has the same effect as typing \\*^S followed by that digit at "
"the beginning of every search pattern.  The value \"-\" disables all default "
"search modifiers."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1978
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--show-preproc-errors>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1983
msgid ""
"If a LESSOPEN preprocessor produces data, then exits with a non-zero exit "
"code, B<less> will display a warning."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1983
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--status-col-width=>I<n>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1988
msgid ""
"Sets the width of the status column when the B<-J> option is in effect.  The "
"default is 2 characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1988
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--status-line>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:1998
msgid ""
"If a line is marked, the entire line (rather than just the status column)  "
"is highlighted.  Also lines highlighted due to the B<-w> option will have "
"the entire line highlighted.  If B<--use-color> is set, the line is colored "
"rather than highlighted."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:1998
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--use-backslash>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2005
msgid ""
"This option changes the interpretations of options which follow this one.  "
"After the B<--use-backslash> option, any backslash in an option string is "
"removed and the following character is taken literally.  This allows a "
"dollar sign to be included in option strings."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2005
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--use-color>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2012
msgid ""
"Enables colored text in various places.  The B<-D> option can be used to "
"change the colors.  Colored text works only if the terminal supports ANSI "
"color escape sequences (as defined in"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2014
msgid "https://\\*:www\\*:.ecma-international\\*:.org/\\*:publications-and-standards/\\*:standards/\\*:ecma-48)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2015
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--wheel-lines=>I<n>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2023
msgid ""
"Set the number of lines to scroll when the mouse wheel is scrolled and the "
"B<--mouse> or B<--MOUSE> option is in effect.  The default is 1 line."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2023
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<--wordwrap>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2030
msgid ""
"When the B<-S> option is not in use, wrap each line at a space or tab if "
"possible, so that a word is not split between two lines.  The default is to "
"wrap at any character."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2030
#, no-wrap
msgid "B<-->"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2039
msgid ""
"A command line argument of \\[dq]B<-->\\[dq] marks the end of option "
"arguments.  Any arguments following this are interpreted as filenames.  This "
"can be useful when viewing a file whose name begins with a \"-\" or \"+\".  "
"Otherwise, option arguments and filename arguments can be intermixed; that "
"is, option arguments do not need to appear before filename arguments, unless "
"the environment variable POSIXLY_CORRECT is set."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2039 original/man1/lesskey.1:308
#, no-wrap
msgid "+"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2057
msgid ""
"If a command line option begins with B<+>, the remainder of that option is "
"taken to be an initial command to B<less>.  For example, +G tells B<less> to "
"start at the end of the file rather than the beginning, and +/xyz tells it "
"to start at the first occurrence of \"xyz\" in the file.  As a special case, "
"+E<lt>numberE<gt> acts like +E<lt>numberE<gt>g; that is, it starts the "
"display at the specified line number (however, see the caveat under the "
"\"g\" command above).  If the option starts with ++, the initial command "
"applies to every file being viewed, not just the first one.  The + command "
"described previously may also be used to set (or change) an initial command "
"for every file.  Also see the B<--cmd> option."
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:2058
#, no-wrap
msgid "LINE EDITING"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2070
msgid ""
"When entering a command line at the bottom of the screen (for example, a "
"filename for the :e command, or the pattern for a search command), certain "
"keys can be used to manipulate the command line.  Most commands have an "
"alternate form in [ brackets ] which can be used if a key does not exist on "
"a particular keyboard.  (Note that the forms beginning with ESC do not work "
"on some MS-DOS and Windows systems because ESC is the line erase character.)  "
"Any of these special keys may be entered literally by preceding it with the "
"\"literal\" character, either \\*^V or \\*^A.  A backslash itself may also "
"be entered literally by entering two backslashes."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2070
#, no-wrap
msgid "LEFTARROW [ ESC-h ]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2072
msgid "Move the cursor one space to the left."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2072
#, no-wrap
msgid "RIGHTARROW [ ESC-l ]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2074
msgid "Move the cursor one space to the right."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2074
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^LEFTARROW [ ESC-b or ESC-LEFTARROW ]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2077
msgid ""
"(That is, CONTROL and LEFTARROW simultaneously.)  Move the cursor one word "
"to the left."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2077
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^RIGHTARROW [ ESC-w or ESC-RIGHTARROW ]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2080
msgid ""
"(That is, CONTROL and RIGHTARROW simultaneously.)  Move the cursor one word "
"to the right."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2080
#, no-wrap
msgid "HOME [ ESC-0 ]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2082
msgid "Move the cursor to the beginning of the line."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2082
#, no-wrap
msgid "END [ ESC-$ ]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2084
msgid "Move the cursor to the end of the line."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2084 original/man1/lesskey.1:88
#, no-wrap
msgid "BACKSPACE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2087
msgid ""
"Delete the character to the left of the cursor, or cancel the command if the "
"command line is empty."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2087
#, no-wrap
msgid "DELETE or [ ESC-x ]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2089
msgid "Delete the character under the cursor."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2089
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^BACKSPACE [ ESC-BACKSPACE ]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2092
msgid ""
"(That is, CONTROL and BACKSPACE simultaneously.)  Delete the word to the "
"left of the cursor."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2092
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^DELETE [ ESC-X or ESC-DELETE ]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2095
msgid ""
"(That is, CONTROL and DELETE simultaneously.)  Delete the word under the "
"cursor."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2095
#, no-wrap
msgid "UPARROW [ ESC-k ]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2099
msgid ""
"Retrieve the previous command line.  If you first enter some text and then "
"press UPARROW, it will retrieve the previous command which begins with that "
"text."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2099
#, no-wrap
msgid "DOWNARROW [ ESC-j ]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2103
msgid ""
"Retrieve the next command line.  If you first enter some text and then press "
"DOWNARROW, it will retrieve the next command which begins with that text."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2103 original/man1/lesskey.1:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "TAB"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2112
msgid ""
"Complete the partial filename to the left of the cursor.  If it matches more "
"than one filename, the first match is entered into the command line.  "
"Repeated TABs will cycle thru the other matching filenames.  If the "
"completed filename is a directory, a \"/\" is appended to the filename.  (On "
"MS-DOS and Windows systems, a \"\\e\" is appended.)  The environment "
"variable LESSSEPARATOR can be used to specify a different character to "
"append to a directory name."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2112
#, no-wrap
msgid "BACKTAB (SHIFT-TAB) [ ESC-TAB ]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2114
msgid "Like TAB, but cycles in the reverse direction thru the matching filenames."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2118
msgid ""
"Complete the partial filename to the left of the cursor.  If it matches more "
"than one filename, all matches are entered into the command line (if they "
"fit)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2118
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^U (Unix and OS/2) or ESC (MS-DOS and Windows)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2123
msgid ""
"Delete the entire command line, or cancel the command if the cursor is at "
"the beginning of the command line.  If you have changed your line-kill "
"character in Unix to something other than \\*^U, that character is used "
"instead of \\*^U."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2123 original/man1/lesskey.1:264
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\*^G"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2125
msgid "Delete the entire command line and return to the main prompt."
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:2126
#, no-wrap
msgid "KEY BINDINGS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2138
msgid ""
"You may define your own B<less> commands by creating a lesskey source file.  "
"This file specifies a set of command keys and an action associated with each "
"key.  You may also change the line-editing keys (see LINE EDITING), and set "
"environment variables used by B<less>.  See the B<lesskey>(1)  manual page "
"for details about the file format."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2160
msgid ""
"If the environment variable LESSKEYIN is set, B<less> uses that as the name "
"of the lesskey source file.  Otherwise, B<less> looks in a standard place "
"for the lesskey source file: On Unix systems, B<less> looks for a lesskey "
"file called \"$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/lesskey\" or \"$HOME/.config/lesskey\" or "
"\"$HOME/.lesskey\".  On MS-DOS and Windows systems, B<less> looks for a "
"lesskey file called \"$HOME/_lesskey\", and if it is not found there, then "
"looks for a lesskey file called \"_lesskey\" in any directory specified in "
"the PATH environment variable.  On OS/2 systems, B<less> looks for a lesskey "
"file called \"$HOME/lesskey.ini\", and if it is not found, then looks for a "
"lesskey file called \"lesskey.ini\" in any directory specified in the INIT "
"environment variable, and if it not found there, then looks for a lesskey "
"file called \"lesskey.ini\" in any directory specified in the PATH "
"environment variable."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2178
msgid ""
"A system-wide lesskey source file may also be set up to provide key "
"bindings.  If a key is defined in both a local lesskey file and in the "
"system-wide file, key bindings in the local file take precedence over those "
"in the system-wide file.  If the environment variable LESSKEYIN_SYSTEM is "
"set, B<less> uses that as the name of the system-wide lesskey file.  "
"Otherwise, B<less> looks in a standard place for the system-wide lesskey "
"file: On Unix systems, the system-wide lesskey file is "
"/usr/local/etc/syslesskey.  (However, if B<less> was built with a different "
"sysconf directory than /usr/local/etc, that directory is where the sysless "
"file is found.)  On MS-DOS and Windows systems, the system-wide lesskey file "
"is c:\\e_syslesskey.  On OS/2 systems, the system-wide lesskey file is "
"c:\\esyslesskey.ini."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2186
msgid ""
"Older versions of B<less> (before v582) used lesskey files with a binary "
"format, produced by the B<lesskey> program. It is no longer necessary to use "
"the B<lesskey> program."
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:2187
#, no-wrap
msgid "INPUT PREPROCESSOR"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2203
msgid ""
"You may define an \"input preprocessor\" for B<less>.  Before B<less> opens "
"a file, it first gives the input preprocessor a chance to modify the way the "
"contents of the file are displayed.  An input preprocessor is simply an "
"executable program (or shell script), which writes the contents of the file "
"to a different file, called the replacement file.  The contents of the "
"replacement file are then displayed in place of the contents of the original "
"file.  However, it will appear to the user as if the original file is "
"opened; that is, B<less> will display the original filename as the name of "
"the current file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2217
msgid ""
"An input preprocessor receives one command line argument, the original "
"filename, as entered by the user.  It should create the replacement file, "
"and when finished, print the name of the replacement file to its standard "
"output.  If the input preprocessor does not output a replacement filename, "
"B<less> uses the original file, as normal.  The input preprocessor is not "
"called when viewing standard input.  To set up an input preprocessor, set "
"the LESSOPEN environment variable to a command line which will invoke your "
"input preprocessor.  This command line should include one occurrence of the "
"string \"%s\", which will be replaced by the filename when the input "
"preprocessor command is invoked."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2232
msgid ""
"When B<less> closes a file opened in such a way, it will call another "
"program, called the input postprocessor, which may perform any desired "
"clean-up action (such as deleting the replacement file created by "
"LESSOPEN).  This program receives two command line arguments, the original "
"filename as entered by the user, and the name of the replacement file.  To "
"set up an input postprocessor, set the LESSCLOSE environment variable to a "
"command line which will invoke your input postprocessor.  It may include two "
"occurrences of the string \"%s\"; the first is replaced with the original "
"name of the file and the second with the name of the replacement file, which "
"was output by LESSOPEN."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2237
msgid ""
"For example, on many Unix systems, these two scripts will allow you to keep "
"files in compressed format, but still let B<less> view them directly:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2239
msgid "lessopen.sh:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2241 original/man1/less.1:2265
#: original/man1/less.1:2300
msgid "  #! /bin/sh"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2243 original/man1/less.1:2302
msgid "  case \"$1\" in"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2245
msgid "  *.Z)\tTEMPFILE=$(mktemp)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2247
msgid "  uncompress -c $1 E<gt>$TEMPFILE 2E<gt>/dev/null"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2249
msgid "  if [ -s $TEMPFILE ]; then"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2251
msgid "  echo $TEMPFILE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2253
msgid "  else"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2255
msgid "  rm -f $TEMPFILE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2257
msgid "  fi"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2259 original/man1/less.1:2306
#: original/man1/less.1:2310
msgid "  ;;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2261 original/man1/less.1:2312
msgid "  esac"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2263
msgid "lessclose.sh:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2267
msgid "  rm $2"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2273
msgid ""
"To use these scripts, put them both where they can be executed and set "
"LESSOPEN=\"lessopen.sh\\ %s\", and LESSCLOSE=\"lessclose.sh\\ %s\\ %s\".  "
"More complex LESSOPEN and LESSCLOSE scripts may be written to accept other "
"types of compressed files, and so on."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2293
msgid ""
"It is also possible to set up an input preprocessor to pipe the file data "
"directly to B<less>, rather than putting the data into a replacement file.  "
"This avoids the need to decompress the entire file before starting to view "
"it.  An input preprocessor that works this way is called an input pipe.  An "
"input pipe, instead of writing the name of a replacement file on its "
"standard output, writes the entire contents of the replacement file on its "
"standard output.  If the input pipe does not write any characters on its "
"standard output, then there is no replacement file and B<less> uses the "
"original file, as normal.  To use an input pipe, make the first character in "
"the LESSOPEN environment variable a vertical bar (|) to signify that the "
"input preprocessor is an input pipe.  As with non-pipe input preprocessors, "
"the command string must contain one occurrence of %s, which is replaced with "
"the filename of the input file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2296
msgid ""
"For example, on many Unix systems, this script will work like the previous "
"example scripts:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2298
msgid "lesspipe.sh:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2304
msgid "  *.Z)\tuncompress -c $1 2E<gt>/dev/null"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2308
msgid "  *)\texit 1"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2314
msgid "  exit $?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2318
msgid ""
"To use this script, put it where it can be executed and set "
"LESSOPEN=\"|lesspipe.sh %s\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2332
msgid ""
"Note that a preprocessor cannot output an empty file, since that is "
"interpreted as meaning there is no replacement, and the original file is "
"used.  To avoid this, if LESSOPEN starts with two vertical bars, the exit "
"status of the script determines the behavior when the output is empty.  If "
"the output is empty and the exit status is zero, the empty output is "
"considered to be replacement text.  If the output is empty and the exit "
"status is nonzero, the original file is used.  For compatibility with "
"previous versions of B<less>, if LESSOPEN starts with only one vertical bar, "
"the exit status of the preprocessor is ignored."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2338
msgid ""
"When an input pipe is used, a LESSCLOSE postprocessor can be used, but it is "
"usually not necessary since there is no replacement file to clean up.  In "
"this case, the replacement file name passed to the LESSCLOSE postprocessor "
"is \"-\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2355
msgid ""
"For compatibility with previous versions of B<less>, the input preprocessor "
"or pipe is not used if B<less> is viewing standard input.  However, if the "
"first character of LESSOPEN is a dash (-), the input preprocessor is used on "
"standard input as well as other files.  In this case, the dash is not "
"considered to be part of the preprocessor command.  If standard input is "
"being viewed, the input preprocessor is passed a file name consisting of a "
"single dash.  Similarly, if the first two characters of LESSOPEN are "
"vertical bar and dash (|-) or two vertical bars and a dash (||-), the input "
"pipe is used on standard input as well as other files.  Again, in this case "
"the dash is not considered to be part of the input pipe command."
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:2356
#, no-wrap
msgid "NATIONAL CHARACTER SETS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2358
msgid "There are five types of characters in the input file:"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2358
#, no-wrap
msgid "normal characters"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2360
msgid "can be displayed directly to the screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2360
#, no-wrap
msgid "control characters"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2363
msgid ""
"should not be displayed directly, but are expected to be found in ordinary "
"text files (such as backspace and tab)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2363
#, no-wrap
msgid "binary characters"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2366
msgid ""
"should not be displayed directly and are not expected to be found in text "
"files."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2366
#, no-wrap
msgid "composing characters"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2369
msgid ""
"are not displayed separately, but modify the display of the preceding "
"character. (Only when LESSCHARSET is \"utf8\".)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2369
#, no-wrap
msgid "deleted characters"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2372
msgid ""
"are simply deleted from the input and not displayed.  (Only when LESSCHARSET "
"is \"utf8\".)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2377
msgid ""
"A \"character set\" is a description of which of these categories each "
"character belongs to.  The LESSCHARSET environment variable may be used to "
"select a character set.  Possible values for LESSCHARSET are:"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2377 original/man1/less.1:2432
#, no-wrap
msgid "ascii"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2381
msgid ""
"BS, TAB, NL, CR, and formfeed are control characters, all chars with values "
"between 32 and 126 are normal, and all others are binary."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2381 original/man1/less.1:2438
#, no-wrap
msgid "iso8859"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2385
msgid ""
"Selects an ISO 8859 character set.  This is the same as ASCII, except "
"characters between 160 and 255 are treated as normal characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2385 original/man1/less.1:2440
#, no-wrap
msgid "latin1"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2387 original/man1/less.1:2389
msgid "Same as iso8859."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2387
#, no-wrap
msgid "latin9"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2389 original/man1/less.1:2433
#, no-wrap
msgid "dos"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2391
msgid "Selects a character set appropriate for MS-DOS."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2391 original/man1/less.1:2434
#, no-wrap
msgid "ebcdic"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2393
msgid "Selects an EBCDIC character set."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2393 original/man1/less.1:2436
#, no-wrap
msgid "IBM-1047"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2398
msgid ""
"Selects an EBCDIC character set used by OS/390 Unix Services.  This is the "
"EBCDIC analogue of latin1.  You get similar results by setting either "
"LESSCHARSET=IBM-1047 or LC_CTYPE=en_US in your environment."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2398 original/man1/less.1:2439
#, no-wrap
msgid "koi8-r"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2400
msgid "Selects a Russian character set."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2400 original/man1/less.1:2441
#, no-wrap
msgid "next"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2402
msgid "Selects a character set appropriate for NeXT computers."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2402
#, no-wrap
msgid "utf-8"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2406
msgid ""
"Selects the UTF-8 encoding of the ISO 10646 character set.  UTF-8 is special "
"in that it supports multi-byte characters in the input file.  It is the only "
"character set that supports multi-byte characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2406
#, no-wrap
msgid "windows"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2408
msgid "Selects a character set appropriate for Microsoft Windows (cp 1252)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2425
msgid ""
"In rare cases, it may be desired to tailor B<less> to use a character set "
"other than the ones definable by LESSCHARSET.  In this case, the environment "
"variable LESSCHARDEF can be used to define a character set.  It should be "
"set to a string where each character in the string represents one character "
"in the character set.  The character \".\\&\" is used for a normal "
"character, \"c\" for control, and \"b\" for binary.  A decimal number may be "
"used for repetition.  For example, \"bccc4b.\\&\" would mean character 0 is "
"binary, 1, 2 and 3 are control, 4, 5, 6 and 7 are binary, and 8 is normal.  "
"All characters after the last are taken to be the same as the last, so "
"characters 9 through 255 would be normal.  (This is an example, and does not "
"necessarily represent any real character set.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2428
msgid ""
"This table shows the value of LESSCHARDEF which is equivalent to each of the "
"possible values for LESSCHARSET:"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2432
#, no-wrap
msgid "8bcccbcc18b95.b"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2433
#, no-wrap
msgid "8bcccbcc12bc5b95.b."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2434
#, no-wrap
msgid "5bc6bcc7bcc41b.9b7.9b5.b..8b6.10b6.b9.7b"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2435
#, no-wrap
msgid "9.8b8.17b3.3b9.7b9.8b8.6b10.b.b.b."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2436
#, no-wrap
msgid "4cbcbc3b9cbccbccbb4c6bcc5b3cbbc4bc4bccbc"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2437
#, no-wrap
msgid "191.b"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2438 original/man1/less.1:2440
#, no-wrap
msgid "8bcccbcc18b95.33b."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2439
#, no-wrap
msgid "8bcccbcc18b95.b128."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2441
#, no-wrap
msgid "8bcccbcc18b95.bb125.bb"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2449
msgid ""
"If neither LESSCHARSET nor LESSCHARDEF is set, but any of the strings "
"\"UTF-8\", \"UTF8\", \"utf-8\" or \"utf8\" is found in the LC_ALL, LC_CTYPE "
"or LANG environment variables, then the default character set is utf-8."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2457
msgid ""
"If that string is not found, but your system supports the B<setlocale>(3)  "
"interface, B<less> will use setlocale to determine the character set.  "
"setlocale is controlled by setting the LANG or LC_CTYPE environment "
"variables."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2461
msgid ""
"Finally, if the B<setlocale> interface is also not available, the default "
"character set is utf-8."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2481
msgid ""
"Control and binary characters are displayed in standout (reverse video).  "
"Each such character is displayed in caret notation if possible (e.g.\\& "
"\\*^A for control-A).  Caret notation is used only if inverting the 0100 bit "
"results in a normal printable character.  Otherwise, the character is "
"displayed as a hex number in angle brackets.  This format can be changed by "
"setting the LESSBINFMT environment variable.  LESSBINFMT may begin with a "
"\"*\" and one character to select the display attribute: \"*k\" is blinking, "
"\"*d\" is bold, \"*u\" is underlined, \"*s\" is standout, and \"*n\" is "
"normal.  If LESSBINFMT does not begin with a \"*\", normal attribute is "
"assumed.  The remainder of LESSBINFMT is a string which may include one "
"printf-style escape sequence (a % followed by x, X, o, d, etc.).  For "
"example, if LESSBINFMT is \"*u[%x]\", binary characters are displayed in "
"underlined hexadecimal surrounded by brackets.  The default if no LESSBINFMT "
"is specified is \"*sE<lt>%02XE<gt>\".  Warning: the result of expanding the "
"character via LESSBINFMT must be less than 31 characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2496
msgid ""
"When the character set is utf-8, the LESSUTFBINFMT environment variable acts "
"similarly to LESSBINFMT but it applies to Unicode code points that were "
"successfully decoded but are unsuitable for display (e.g., unassigned code "
"points).  Its default value is \"E<lt>U+%04lXE<gt>\".  Note that "
"LESSUTFBINFMT and LESSBINFMT share their display attribute setting (\"*x\") "
"so specifying one will affect both; LESSUTFBINFMT is read after LESSBINFMT "
"so its setting, if any, will have priority.  Problematic octets in a UTF-8 "
"file (octets of a truncated sequence, octets of a complete but non-shortest "
"form sequence, invalid octets, and stray trailing octets)  are displayed "
"individually using LESSBINFMT so as to facilitate diagnostic of how the "
"UTF-8 file is ill-formed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2517
msgid ""
"When the character set is utf-8, in rare cases it may be desirable to "
"override the Unicode definition of the type of certain characters.  For "
"example, characters in a Private Use Area are normally treated as binary "
"characters, but if you are using a custom font with printable characters in "
"that range, it may be desirable to tell B<less> to treat such characters as "
"printable.  This can be done by setting the LESSUTFCHARDEF environment "
"variable to a comma-separated list of I<character type> definitions.  Each "
"character type definition consists of either one hexadecimal codepoint or a "
"pair of codepoints separated by a dash, followed by a colon and a type "
"character.  Each hexadecimal codepoint may optionally be preceded by a \"U\" "
"or \"U+\".  If a pair of codepoints is given, the type is set for all "
"characters inclusively between the two values.  If there are multiple "
"comma-separated codepoint values, they must be in ascending numerical "
"order.  The type character may be one of:"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2518 original/man1/lesskey.1:238
#, no-wrap
msgid "p"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2520
msgid "A normal printable character."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2522
msgid "A wide (2-space) printable character."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2524
msgid "A binary (non-printable) character."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2526
msgid "A composing (zero width) character."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2528
msgid "A deleted character (deleted from the input and not displayed)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2531
msgid "For example, setting LESSUTFCHARDEF to"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2535
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tE000-F8FF:p,F0000-FFFFD:p,100000-10FFFD:p\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2539
msgid "would make all Private Use Area characters be treated as printable."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2546
msgid ""
"By default, emoji modifiers, components and variation selectors are deleted "
"because many terminals do not display them correctly.  If you use a terminal "
"which does display some or all of them correctly, you can cause them to be "
"displayed by setting LESSUTFCHARDEF to treat them as composing characters.  "
"For example, this sets them all to composing characters:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2550
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tFE00-FE0F:c,1F3FB-1F3FF:c,1F9B0-1F9B3:c,E0100-E01EF:c\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:2552
#, no-wrap
msgid "PROMPTS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2563
msgid ""
"The B<-P> option allows you to tailor the prompt to your preference.  The "
"string given to the B<-P> option replaces the specified prompt string.  "
"Certain characters in the string are interpreted specially.  The prompt "
"mechanism is rather complicated to provide flexibility, but the ordinary "
"user need not understand the details of constructing personalized prompt "
"strings."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2568
msgid ""
"A percent sign followed by a single character is expanded according to what "
"the following character is.  (References to the input file size below refer "
"to the preprocessed size, if an input preprocessor is being used.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2568
#, no-wrap
msgid "%bI<X>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2580
msgid ""
"Replaced by the byte offset into the current input file.  The b is followed "
"by a single character (shown as I<X> above)  which specifies the line whose "
"byte offset is to be used.  If the character is a \"t\", the byte offset of "
"the top line in the display is used, an \"m\" means use the middle line, a "
"\"b\" means use the bottom line, a \"B\" means use the line just after the "
"bottom line, and a \"j\" means use the \"target\" line, as specified by the "
"B<-j> option."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2580
#, no-wrap
msgid "%B"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2582
msgid "Replaced by the size of the current input file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2582
#, no-wrap
msgid "%c"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2585
msgid ""
"Replaced by the column number of the text which appears in the first column "
"of the screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2585
#, no-wrap
msgid "%C"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2588
msgid ""
"Replaced by the column number of the text which appears (or would appear) in "
"the last column of the screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2588
#, no-wrap
msgid "%dI<X>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2591
msgid ""
"Replaced by the page number of a line in the input file.  The line to be "
"used is determined by the I<X>, as with the %b option."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2591
#, no-wrap
msgid "%D"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2594
msgid ""
"Replaced by the number of pages in the input file, or equivalently, the page "
"number of the last line in the input file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2594
#, no-wrap
msgid "%E"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2598
msgid ""
"Replaced by the name of the editor (from the VISUAL environment variable, or "
"the EDITOR environment variable if VISUAL is not defined).  See the "
"discussion of the LESSEDIT feature below."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2598
#, no-wrap
msgid "%f"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2600
msgid "Replaced by the name of the current input file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2600
#, no-wrap
msgid "%F"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2602
msgid "Replaced by the last component of the name of the current input file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2602
#, no-wrap
msgid "%g"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2606
msgid ""
"Replaced by the shell-escaped name of the current input file.  This is "
"useful when the expanded string will be used in a shell command, such as in "
"LESSEDIT."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2606
#, no-wrap
msgid "%i"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2609
msgid "Replaced by the index of the current file in the list of input files."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2609
#, no-wrap
msgid "%lI<X>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2612
msgid ""
"Replaced by the line number of a line in the input file.  The line to be "
"used is determined by the I<X>, as with the %b option."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2612
#, no-wrap
msgid "%L"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2614
msgid "Replaced by the line number of the last line in the input file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2614
#, no-wrap
msgid "%m"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2616
msgid "Replaced by the total number of input files."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2616
#, no-wrap
msgid "%o"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2620
msgid ""
"Replaced by the URI of the currently selected OSC 8 hyperlink, or a question "
"mark if no hyperlink is selected.  This is used by OSC 8 handlers as "
"explained in the \\*^O\\*^O command description."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2620
#, no-wrap
msgid "%pI<X>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2623
msgid ""
"Replaced by the percent into the current input file, based on byte offsets.  "
"The line used is determined by the I<X> as with the %b option."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2623
#, no-wrap
msgid "%PI<X>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2626
msgid ""
"Replaced by the percent into the current input file, based on line numbers.  "
"The line used is determined by the I<X> as with the %b option."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2626
#, no-wrap
msgid "%Q"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2631
msgid ""
"Replaced by the percent of the last column of text displayed on the screen "
"compared to the length of the longest line currently displayed (that is, %C "
"divided by %W).  Note that using this sequence can make displaying the "
"prompt be slower than usual."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2631
#, no-wrap
msgid "%s"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2633
msgid "Same as %B."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2633
#, no-wrap
msgid "%t"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2636
msgid ""
"Causes any trailing spaces to be removed.  Usually used at the end of the "
"string, but may appear anywhere."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2636
#, no-wrap
msgid "%T"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2642
msgid ""
"Normally expands to the word \"file\".  However if viewing files via a tags "
"list using the B<-t> option, it expands to the word \"tag\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2642
#, no-wrap
msgid "%W"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2645
msgid ""
"Replaced by the width of the longest line currently displayed on the "
"screen.  Note that using this sequence can make displaying the prompt be "
"slower than usual."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2645
#, no-wrap
msgid "%x"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2647
msgid "Replaced by the name of the next input file in the list."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2650
msgid ""
"If any item is unknown (for example, the file size if input is a pipe), a "
"question mark is printed instead."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2663
msgid ""
"The format of the prompt string can be changed depending on certain "
"conditions.  A question mark followed by a single character acts like an "
"\"IF\": depending on the following character, a condition is evaluated.  If "
"the condition is true, any characters following the question mark and "
"condition character, up to a period, are included in the prompt.  If the "
"condition is false, such characters are not included.  A colon appearing "
"between the question mark and the period can be used to establish an "
"\"ELSE\": any characters between the colon and the period are included in "
"the string if and only if the IF condition is false.  Condition characters "
"(which follow a question mark) may be:"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2663
#, no-wrap
msgid "?a"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2665
msgid "True if any characters have been included in the prompt so far."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2665
#, no-wrap
msgid "?bI<X>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2667
msgid "True if the byte offset of the specified line is known."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2667
#, no-wrap
msgid "?B"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2669
msgid "True if the size of current input file is known."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2669
#, no-wrap
msgid "?c"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2671
msgid "True if the text is horizontally shifted (%c is not zero)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2671
#, no-wrap
msgid "?dI<X>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2673
msgid "True if the page number of the specified line is known."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2673
#, no-wrap
msgid "?e"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2675
msgid "True if at end-of-file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2675
#, no-wrap
msgid "?f"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2678
msgid "True if there is an input filename (that is, if input is not a pipe)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2678
#, no-wrap
msgid "?lI<X>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2680
msgid "True if the line number of the specified line is known."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2680
#, no-wrap
msgid "?L"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2682
msgid "True if the line number of the last line in the file is known."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2682
#, no-wrap
msgid "?m"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2684
msgid "True if there is more than one input file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2684
#, no-wrap
msgid "?n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2686
msgid "True if this is the first prompt in a new input file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2686
#, no-wrap
msgid "?pI<X>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2689
msgid ""
"True if the percent into the current input file, based on byte offsets, of "
"the specified line is known."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2689
#, no-wrap
msgid "?PI<X>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2692
msgid ""
"True if the percent into the current input file, based on line numbers, of "
"the specified line is known."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2692
#, no-wrap
msgid "?Q"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2695
msgid ""
"True if %Q is less than 100.  Note that using this sequence can make "
"displaying the prompt be slower than usual."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2695
#, no-wrap
msgid "?s"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2697
msgid "Same as \"?B\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2697
#, no-wrap
msgid "?x"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2700
msgid ""
"True if there is a next input file (that is, if the current input file is "
"not the last one)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2706
msgid ""
"Any characters other than the special ones (question mark, colon, period, "
"percent, and backslash)  become literally part of the prompt.  Any of the "
"special characters may be included in the prompt literally by preceding it "
"with a backslash."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2708
msgid "Some examples:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2711
#, no-wrap
msgid "?f%f:Standard input.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2715
msgid ""
"This prompt prints the filename, if known; otherwise the string \"Standard "
"input\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2718
#, no-wrap
msgid "?f%f \\&.?ltLine %lt:?pt%pt\\e%:?btByte %bt:-...\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2727
msgid ""
"This prompt would print the filename, if known.  The filename is followed by "
"the line number, if known, otherwise the percent if known, otherwise the "
"byte offset if known.  Otherwise, a dash is printed.  Notice how each "
"question mark has a matching period, and how the % after the %pt is included "
"literally by escaping it with a backslash."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2730
#, no-wrap
msgid "?n?f%f\\ .?m(%T %i of %m)\\ ..?e(END)\\ ?x-\\ Next\\e:\\ %x..%t\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2746
msgid ""
"This prints the filename if this is the first prompt in a file, followed by "
"the \"file N of N\" message if there is more than one input file.  Then, if "
"we are at end-of-file, the string \"(END)\" is printed followed by the name "
"of the next file, if there is one.  Finally, any trailing spaces are "
"truncated.  This is the default prompt.  For reference, here are the "
"defaults for the other two prompts B<-m> and B<-M> respectively).  Each is "
"broken into two lines here for readability only."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2751
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"?n?f%f\\ .?m(%T\\ %i\\ of\\ %m)\\ ..?e(END)\\ ?x-\\ Next\\e:\\ %x.:\n"
"\t?pB%pB\\e%:byte\\ %bB?s/%s...%t\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2754
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"?f%f\\ .?n?m(%T\\ %i\\ of\\ %m)\\ ..?ltlines\\ %lt-%lb?L/%L.\\ :\n"
"\tbyte\\ %bB?s/%s.\\ .?e(END)\\ ?x-\\ Next\\e:\\ %x.:?pB%pB\\e%..?c\\ "
"(column\\ %c).%t\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2758
msgid "And here is the default message produced by the = command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2763
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"?f%f\\ .?m(%T\\ %i\\ of\\ %m)\\ .?ltlines\\ %lt-%lb?L/%L.\\ .\n"
"\tbyte\\ %bB?s/%s.\\ ?e(END)\\ :?pB%pB\\e%..?c\\ (column\\ %c).%t\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2771
msgid ""
"The prompt expansion features are also used for another purpose: if an "
"environment variable LESSEDIT is defined, it is used as the command to be "
"executed when the v command is invoked.  The LESSEDIT string is expanded in "
"the same way as the prompt strings.  The default value for LESSEDIT is:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2775
#, no-wrap
msgid "\t%E\\ ?lm+%lm.\\ %g\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2783
msgid ""
"Note that this expands to the editor name, followed by a + and the line "
"number, followed by the shell-escaped file name.  If your editor does not "
"accept the \"+linenumber\" syntax, or has other differences in invocation "
"syntax, the LESSEDIT variable can be changed to modify this default."
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:2784
#, no-wrap
msgid "SECURITY"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2789
msgid ""
"When the environment variable LESSSECURE is set to 1, B<less> runs in a "
"\"secure\" mode.  In this mode, these features are disabled:"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2789
#, no-wrap
msgid "edit"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2791
msgid "the edit command (v)"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2791 original/man1/lesskey.1:280
#: original/man1/lesskey.1:281 original/man1/lesskey.1:282
#, no-wrap
msgid "examine"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2793
msgid "the examine command (:e)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2793
#, no-wrap
msgid "glob"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2795
msgid "metacharacters such as * in filenames,"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2797
msgid "and filename completion (TAB, \\*^L)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2797
#, no-wrap
msgid "history"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2799
msgid "history file"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2799
#, no-wrap
msgid "lesskey"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2804
msgid "use of lesskey files B<-k> and B<--lesskey-src>)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2804
#, no-wrap
msgid "lessopen"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2806
msgid "input preprocessor (LESSOPEN environment variable)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2806
#, no-wrap
msgid "logfile"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2809
msgid "log files (s and B<-o>)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2809
#, no-wrap
msgid "osc8"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2811
msgid "opening OSC 8 links (\\*^O\\*^O)"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2811 original/man1/lesskey.1:304
#, no-wrap
msgid "pipe"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2813
msgid "the pipe command (|)"
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2813 original/man1/lesskey.1:306
#, no-wrap
msgid "shell"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2815
msgid "the shell and pshell commands (! and #)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2815
#, no-wrap
msgid "stop"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2819
msgid "stopping B<less> via a SIGTSTP signal"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2819
#, no-wrap
msgid "tags"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2822
msgid "use of tags files (B<-t>)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2828
msgid ""
"The LESSSECURE_ALLOW environment variable can be set to a comma-separated "
"list of names of features which are selectively enabled when LESSSECURE is "
"set.  Each feature name is the first word in each line in the above list.  A "
"feature name may be abbreviated as long as the abbreviation is unambiguous.  "
"For example, if"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2830
msgid "LESSSECURE=1"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2832
msgid "and"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2834
msgid "LESSSECURE_ALLOW=hist,edit"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2837
msgid ""
"were set, all of the above features would be disabled except for history "
"files and the edit command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2840
msgid ""
"Less can also be compiled to be permanently in \"secure\" mode.  In that "
"case, the LESSSECURE and LESSSECURE_ALLOW variables are ignored."
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:2841
#, no-wrap
msgid "COMPATIBILITY WITH MORE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2852
msgid ""
"If the environment variable LESS_IS_MORE is set to 1, or if the program is "
"invoked via a file link named \"more\" and the environment variable "
"LESS_IS_MORE is not set to 0, B<less> behaves (mostly) in conformance with "
"the POSIX B<more>(1)  command specification.  In this mode, B<less> behaves "
"differently in these ways:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2870
msgid ""
"The B<-e> option works differently.  If the B<-e> option is not set, B<less> "
"behaves as if the B<-e> option were set.  If the B<-e> option is set, "
"B<less> behaves as if the B<-E> option were set."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2881
msgid ""
"The B<-m> option works differently.  If the B<-m> option is not set, the "
"medium prompt is used, and it is prefixed with the string \"--More--\".  If "
"the B<-m> option is set, the short prompt is used."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2890
msgid ""
"The B<-n> option acts like the B<-z> option.  The normal behavior of the "
"B<-n> option is unavailable in this mode."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2896
msgid ""
"The parameter to the B<-p> option is taken to be a B<less> command rather "
"than a search pattern."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2899
msgid ""
"The LESS environment variable is ignored, and the MORE environment variable "
"is used in its place."
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:2900
#, no-wrap
msgid "ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2909
msgid ""
"Environment variables may be specified either in the system environment as "
"usual, or in a B<lesskey>(1)  file.  If environment variables are defined in "
"more than one place, variables defined in a local lesskey file take "
"precedence over variables defined in the system environment, which take "
"precedence over variables defined in the system-wide lesskey file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2909
#, no-wrap
msgid "COLUMNS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2915
msgid ""
"Sets the number of columns on the screen.  Takes precedence over the number "
"of columns specified by the TERM variable.  (But if you have a windowing "
"system which supports TIOCGWINSZ or WIOCGETD, the window system's idea of "
"the screen size takes precedence over the LINES and COLUMNS environment "
"variables.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2915
#, no-wrap
msgid "EDITOR"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2917 original/man1/less.1:3173
msgid "The name of the editor (used for the v command)."
msgstr ""

#. type: tbl table
#: original/man1/less.1:2917 original/man1/lesskey.1:108
#, no-wrap
msgid "HOME"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2920
msgid ""
"Name of the user's home directory (used to find a lesskey file on Unix and "
"OS/2 systems)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2920
#, no-wrap
msgid "HOMEDRIVE, HOMEPATH"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2924
msgid ""
"Concatenation of the HOMEDRIVE and HOMEPATH environment variables is the "
"name of the user's home directory if the HOME variable is not set (only in "
"the Windows version)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2924
#, no-wrap
msgid "INIT"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2926
msgid ""
"Name of the user's init directory (used to find a lesskey file on OS/2 "
"systems)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2926
#, no-wrap
msgid "LANG"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2928 original/man1/less.1:2930
msgid "Language for determining the character set."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2928
#, no-wrap
msgid "LC_CTYPE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2934
msgid "Options which are passed to B<less> automatically."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2934
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSANSIENDCHARS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2937
msgid "Characters which may end an ANSI color escape sequence (default \"m\")."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2937
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSANSIMIDCHARS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2941
msgid ""
"Characters which may appear between the ESC character and the end character "
"in an ANSI color escape sequence (default \"0123456789:;[?!\"\\*'#%()*+\\ "
"\")."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2941
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSANSIOSCALLOW"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2947
msgid ""
"A comma-separated list of OSC types which are output directly to the "
"terminal when B<-R> is in effect (default \"8\"; that is, only OSC 8 "
"sequences are output directly)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2947
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSANSIOSCCHARS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2958
msgid ""
"Characters which may follow an ESC character to mark the start of an \"OS "
"Command\" sequence.  All characters that follow this character up to a "
"String Terminator (ESC-backslash or BEL)  are considered to be part of the "
"OSC sequence (default \"]\").  If a character in LESSANSIOSCCHARS is "
"followed by an asterisk, sequences that begin with that character in the "
"file contents are passed through to the terminal; otherwise only sequences "
"that appear in a prompt string are passed through."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2958
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSBINFMT"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2960
msgid "Format for displaying non-printable, non-control characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2960
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSCHARDEF"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2962
msgid "Defines a character set."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2962
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSCHARSET"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2964
msgid "Selects a predefined character set."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2964
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSCLOSE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2966
msgid "Command line to invoke the (optional) input-postprocessor."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2966
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSECHO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2970
msgid ""
"Name of the lessecho program (default \"lessecho\").  The lessecho program "
"is needed to expand metacharacters, such as * and ?, in filenames on Unix "
"systems."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2970
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSEDIT"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2973
msgid ""
"Editor prototype string (used for the v command).  See discussion under "
"PROMPTS."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2973
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSGLOBALTAGS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2980
msgid ""
"Name of the command used by the B<-t> option to find global tags.  Normally "
"should be set to \"global\" if your system has the B<global>(1)  command.  "
"If not set, global tags are not used."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2980
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSHISTFILE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2986
msgid ""
"Name of the history file used to remember search commands and shell commands "
"between invocations of B<less>.  If set to \"-\" or \"/dev/null\", a history "
"file is not used.  The default depends on the operating system, but is "
"usually:"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2987
#, no-wrap
msgid "Linux and Unix"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2990
msgid ""
"\"$XDG_STATE_HOME/lesshst\" or \"$HOME/.local/state/lesshst\" or "
"\"$XDG_DATA_HOME/lesshst\" or \"$HOME/.lesshst\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2990
#, no-wrap
msgid "Windows and MS-DOS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2992
msgid "\"$HOME/_lesshst\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2992
#, no-wrap
msgid "OS/2"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2994
msgid "\"$HOME/lesshst.ini\" or \"$INIT/lesshst.ini\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2995
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSHISTSIZE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:2998
msgid ""
"The maximum number of commands to save in the history file.  The default is "
"100."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:2998
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSKEYIN"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3002
msgid "Name of the default I<lesskey source> file."
msgstr ""

#. type: TH
#: original/man1/less.1:3002 original/man1/lesskey.1:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSKEY"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3006
msgid ""
"Name of the default I<lesskey binary> file. (Not used if \"$LESSKEYIN\" "
"exists.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3006
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSKEY_CONTENT"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3010
msgid ""
"The value is parsed as if it were the parameter of a B<--lesskey-content> "
"option."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3010
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSKEYIN_SYSTEM"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3014
msgid "Name of the default system-wide I<lesskey source> file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3014
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSKEY_SYSTEM"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3018
msgid ""
"Name of the default system-wide I<lesskey binary> file. (Not used if "
"\"$LESSKEYIN_SYSTEM\" exists.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3018
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSMETACHARS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3020
msgid "List of characters which are considered \"metacharacters\" by the shell."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3020
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSMETAESCAPE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3023
msgid ""
"Prefix which less will add before each metacharacter in a command sent to "
"the shell (default \"\\e\")."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3023
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSNOCONFIG"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3031
msgid ""
"If set to \"-\", all environment variables except TERM are ignored (treated "
"as if they were not set).  If set to a comma-separated list of environment "
"variable names, all environment variables except TERM and those in the list "
"are ignored.  In either case (if set to any non-empty value), all B<lesskey> "
"files are also ignored."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3031
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSOPEN"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3033
msgid "Command line to invoke the (optional) input-preprocessor."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3033
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSSECURE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3036
msgid "Runs less in \"secure\" mode.  See discussion under SECURITY."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3036
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSSECURE_ALLOW"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3039
msgid ""
"Enables individual features which are normally disabled by LESSSECURE.  See "
"discussion under SECURITY."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3039
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSSEPARATOR"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3042
msgid ""
"String to be appended to a directory name in filename completion (default "
"\"\\e\" on MS-DOS, Windows, and OS/2; otherwise \"/\")."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3042
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSUTFBINFMT"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3044
msgid "Format for displaying non-printable Unicode code points."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3044
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESSUTFCHARDEF"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3046
msgid "Overrides the type of specified Unicode characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3046
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_COLUMNS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3054
msgid ""
"Sets the number of columns on the screen.  Unlike COLUMNS, takes precedence "
"over the system's idea of the screen size, so it can be used to make B<less> "
"use less than the full screen width.  If set to a negative number, sets the "
"number of columns used to this much less than the actual screen width."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3054
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_LINES"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3066
msgid ""
"Sets the number of lines on the screen.  Unlike LINES, takes precedence over "
"the system's idea of the screen size, so it can be used to make B<less> use "
"less than the full screen height.  If set to a negative number, sets the "
"number of lines used to this much less than the actual screen height.  When "
"set, B<less> repaints the entire screen on every movement command, so "
"scrolling may be slower."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3066
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_DATA_DELAY"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3070
msgid ""
"Duration (in milliseconds) after starting to read data from the input, after "
"which the \"Waiting for data\" message will be displayed.  The default is "
"4000 (4 seconds)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3070
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_IS_MORE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3074
msgid "Emulate the B<more>(1)  command."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3074
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_OSC8_xxx"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3077
msgid ""
"Where \"xxx\" is a URI scheme such as \"http\" or \"file\", sets an OSC 8 "
"handler for opening OSC 8 links containing a URI with that scheme."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3077
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_OSC8_ANY"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3080
msgid ""
"Sets an OSC 8 handler for opening OSC 8 links for which there is no specific "
"LESS_OSC8_xxx handler set for the \"xxx\" scheme."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3080
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_SHELL_LINES"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3094
msgid ""
"When the B<-F> option is set, B<less> exits automatically if the number of "
"screen lines used to display the file is less than or equal to the screen "
"height minus the value of the LESS_SHELL_LINES variable.  Thus, if you use a "
"shell prompt which occupies more than one screen line, this variable can be "
"set to the number of lines used by your prompt, to ensure that the entire "
"file can be seen when B<-F> is used.  If not set, LESS_SHELL_LINES is "
"assumed to be 1."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3094
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_SIGUSR1"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3100
msgid ""
"If set to a string of one or more B<less> command characters, those commands "
"will be executed when B<less> receives a SIGUSR1 signal."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3100
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_TERMCAP_xx"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3105
msgid ""
"Where \"xx\" is any two characters, overrides the definition of the termcap "
"\"xx\" capability for the terminal.  No escape sequences in the string are "
"processed, so any nonprintable characters such as ESC must be in the string "
"literally."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3105
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_TERMINFO_xxxx"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3116
msgid ""
"Where \"xxxx\" is any string of characters, overrides the definition of the "
"terminfo \"xxxx\" capability for the terminal.  You can use either "
"LESS_TERMCAP_xx or LESS_TERMINFO_xxxx to override a terminal capability, "
"regardless of whether B<less> is built with the B<termcap> or the "
"B<terminfo> library."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3116
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_TERMCAP_BRACKETED_PASTE_START"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3121
msgid ""
"Overrides the standard ANSI escape sequence to enable bracketed paste.  This "
"is used when the B<--no-paste> option is in effect."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3121
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_TERMCAP_BRACKETED_PASTE_END"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3123
msgid "Overrides the standard ANSI escape sequence to disable bracketed paste."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3123
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_TERMCAP_MOUSE_START"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3128
msgid ""
"Overrides the standard ANSI escape sequence to enable mouse reporting.  This "
"is used when the B<--mouse> option is in effect."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3128
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_TERMCAP_MOUSE_END"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3130
msgid "Overrides the standard ANSI escape sequence to disable mouse reporting."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3130
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_TERMCAP_SUSPEND"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3135
msgid ""
"Defines an escape sequence to temporarily suspend screen updates.  This is "
"sent to the terminal before clearing the screen.  This can be used to avoid "
"screen tearing when the screen is redrawn on certain terminals."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3135
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_TERMCAP_RESUME"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3138
msgid ""
"Defines an escape sequence to resume screen updates.  This is sent to the "
"terminal after displaying the prompt."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3138
#, no-wrap
msgid "LESS_UNSUPPORT"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3145
msgid ""
"A space-separated list of command line options.  These options will be "
"ignored (with no error message) if they appear on the command line or in the "
"LESS environment variable.  Options listed in LESS_UNSUPPORT can still be "
"changed by the - and -- commands.  Each option in LESS_UNSUPPORT is a dash "
"followed by a single character option letter, or two dashes followed by a "
"long option name."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3145
#, no-wrap
msgid "LINES"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3151
msgid ""
"Sets the number of lines on the screen.  Takes precedence over the number of "
"lines specified by the TERM variable.  (But if you have a windowing system "
"which supports TIOCGWINSZ or WIOCGETD, the window system's idea of the "
"screen size takes precedence over the LINES and COLUMNS environment "
"variables.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3151
#, no-wrap
msgid "MORE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3156
msgid ""
"Options which are passed to B<less> automatically when running in "
"B<more>-compatible mode."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3156
#, no-wrap
msgid "PATH"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3159
msgid ""
"User's search path (used to find a lesskey file on MS-DOS, Windows, and OS/2 "
"systems)."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3159
#, no-wrap
msgid "POSIXLY_CORRECT"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3165
msgid ""
"If set to any value, all option arguments on the command line are expected "
"to appear before any filename arguments.  This must be set as an actual "
"environment variable, not in a B<lesskey> file."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3165
#, no-wrap
msgid "SHELL"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3167
msgid "The shell used to execute the !\\& command, as well as to expand filenames."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3167
#, no-wrap
msgid "TERM"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3171
msgid "The type of terminal on which B<less> is being run."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3171
#, no-wrap
msgid "VISUAL"
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3173
#, no-wrap
msgid "XDG_CONFIG_HOME"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3177
msgid "Possible location of the B<lesskey> file; see the KEY BINDINGS section."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3177
#, no-wrap
msgid "XDG_DATA_HOME"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3179 original/man1/less.1:3181
msgid ""
"Possible location of the history file; see the description of the "
"LESSHISTFILE environment variable."
msgstr ""

#. type: IP
#: original/man1/less.1:3179
#, no-wrap
msgid "XDG_STATE_HOME"
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: original/man1/less.1:3182 original/man1/lesskey.1:552
#, no-wrap
msgid "SEE ALSO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: original/man1/less.1:3185
msgid "B<lesskey>(1), B<lessecho>(1)"
msgstr ""

